INSERT INTO `zh_search` VALUES (254,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch06-UsersSecurity/02-RptFrmSecurity.html','06.02','Reports/Forms Security','Reports/Forms Security     Reports/Forms Security  Phreebooks reports and forms have three levels of security: user, employee, and department. They my be used individually or in any combination.  User security - One or more (or all by default) users may be given access to the report.  Employee - One of more (or all by default) employees may be given access to the report. Department - one or more (or all by default) departments may be given access to the report. &nbsp;'),(255,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch06-UsersSecurity/01-CtlPanelSecurity.html','06.01','Control Panel Security','Control Panel Security     Control Panel Security The Phreebooks control panel has built in security to control user access to individual control panel modules. Permissions are based on the modules most closely related to the PhreeBooks module it pertains to. For example, the sales order control panel module is tied to the permission of the Customer-&gt;Sales Orders module. If the user has no access to the Sales Order function, the control panel module will be blocked as well.  &nbsp;'),(256,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch06-UsersSecurity/UsersMain.html','06','Users and Security','Users and Security\r \r \r \r \r Users and Security\r Phreebooks support multiple users each assigned multi-level  security. During setup, the administrator user is defined and given full privileges. the administrator can then add additional users and set security appropriately. Each module has an unique securty id and can be set to the following levels:\r \r   None - No access. Users with this security will not see the module as part of the menu.\r   Read Only - The user can only open and read the information. they are not permitted to save and changes they make to the record. In this case, the Save icon will not be displayed.\r   Add - The user can create records but cannot edit them or delete them.\r   Edit - The user can add and edit a record but cannot delete the record. \r   Full - The user has full read/write access to the record.\r \r The add/edit a user:\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Users.\r   The current users are listed. To edit a user, select the Edit icon for the user to edit, or, to enter a new user press the Add button.\r    Enter/edit the fields as necessary. Enter the security levels for each module as necessary. \r     NOTE: If editting a user and  the passwords fields are left blank, the password will not be affected.\r     NOTE: \r   Users may be linked to the employee list only if the employee us set up prior to the user account. \r   Press the Save icon to save the record. NOTE: the user settings will not take effect until the user logs off and back onto the system.\r \r To delete a user:\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Users.\r   The current users are listed. To delete a user, select the Delete icon for the user to delete.\r   Confirm you choice and the user will be removed from the database.\r \r &nbsp;'),(257,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/UserManualHome.html','07','User Manual','User Manual     PhreeBooks Users Manual Please select a category to view: Vendors - Your suppliers of goods and services.  Customers - Those that receive you companies goods and services.  Inventory - The goods and services your company produces/sells. Banking - Your financial receivables (customer payments), payables ( customer payments) and activities related to your financial institution.  General Ledger - The accounting ledgers to track your companies overall performance. Employees - Your companies work force, sales reps, and other personnel used to operate your company.  Setup - Defines the modules activated, security settings, and other parameters needed to tailor PhreeBooks to you company.  Configuration and Defaults - Sets the default information to use throughout PhreeBooks. Defined default general ledger accounts, required information, and other initial settings used.'),(258,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/09-Configuration/01-ControlPanel.html','07.09.01','Control Panel','Control Panel     Control Panel &nbsp;'),(259,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/09-Configuration/ConfigHome.html','07.09','Configuration','Configuration     Configuration &nbsp;'),(260,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/01-Languages/LanguagesHome.html','07.08.01','Setup - Languages','Setup - Languages     Setup - Languages Phreebooks is designed for multi-language capability. The standard release includes translations for English (US). Language modules, as they come available, are available at the PhreeBooks website. Prior to login, the directory /modules/general/language is read and all loaded language modules will appear in a drop down at login. Once a language is selected, it is stored in a session variable and will remain in effect unitl the user logs out.'),(261,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/SetupHome.html','07.08','Setup','Setup Home     Setup Home Company setup modules allow for customization of PhreeBooks to meet the needs of your business. Several modules are included with the standard release of PhreeBooks but others may be available for download at www.PhreeBooks.com. the standard modules include: Languages Currencies Sales Tax Countries States/Provinces Branches Shipping Payment Price Sheets ZenCart Interface User Maintenance &nbsp;'),(262,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/01-ImportData.html','07.08.06.01','Importing Data','Importing Data\r \r \r \r \r Importing Data\r Data can be imported into PhreeBooks such as customers, vendors, and inventory. \r The HOW TOs contain samples of import procedures to import customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing/Exporting Overview\r   Exporting Data from PhreeBooks'),(263,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/02-ExportData.html','07.08.06.02','Exporting Data','Exporting Data\r \r \r \r \r Exporting Data\r Data can be exported from PhreeBooks to text files for use in other applications. \r The HOW TOs contain samples of export procedures to export customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing/Exporting Overview\r   Importing Data into PhreeBooks'),(264,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/ImpExpHome.html','07.08.06','Importing/Exporting Data','Importing/Exporting Data\r \r \r \r \r Importing and Exporting Data\r PhreeBooks has a powerful import/export tool to transfer data in to/out of the PhreeBooks database. Knowledge of the PhreeBooks database structure and data fields are necessary to acurately import information into the database. Exporting is less complicated but still required some knowledge of the database tables. \r Most import/export operations deal solely with a single database table. The exception is the account definitions (customers, vendors, branches). These definitions include the address book fields (currently set at 5) with the main account information.\r Other import scripts specialized towards beginning balance initialization can be found here.\r The HOW TOs contain samples of import procedures to import customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing Data into PhreeBooks\r   Exporting Data from PhreeBooks'),(265,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/01-TaxAuthorities.html','07.08.03.01','Setup - Sales Tax Authorities','Setup - Sales Tax Authorities\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax Authorities\r Sales tax authorities can be set for one or more Tax Authorities. they can be assigned a different collection account to help facilitate tracking and payment of taxes collected. Sales tax authorities need to be set up prior to setting up sales tax rates.\r Adding a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the New icon. A popup will appear with a form to fill out.\r   Enter a short name for the taxing authority, e.g. state tax, city tax, vat, etc.\r   Enter a more detailed description of the taxing authority.\r   Enter the general ledger account to track taxes collected for this authority.\r    If the vendor is in the database, select the vendor to use to send payment to when submitting the taxes to the authority.\r    Enter the tax rate in percent, e.g. 7.2, 15.0, etc. Use a decimal point (.) for non-integer percentages.\r   Press the Save icon to add the sales tax authority to the database.\r \r Editing a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the sales tax authority to edit. A popup will appear with a form pre-filled with the current data.\r   Make any necessary changes and press the Save icon to update the sales tax authority in the database.\r   \r Deleting a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the sales tax authority to Delete. A confirmation popup will appear.\r   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the sales tax authority will be removed from the  database.\r \r Related Links\r Sales Tax Overview\r   Sales Tax Rates \r Adding a Vendor Account\r   Adding a General Ledger Account'),(266,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/02-TaxRates.html','07.08.03.02','Setup - Sales Tax Rates','Setup - Sales Tax Rates\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax Rates\r Sales tax rates can be set at several levels depending on the taxing structure of your business. Prior to setting up sales tax rates, sales tax authorities need to be set up. Refer the the help file on Sales Tax Authorities for more information.\r Adding a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the New icon. A popup will appear with a form to fill out.\r   Enter a short name for the tax rate, e.g. Local Tax, State TAX, VAT, etc.\r   Enter a more detailed description of the tax rate.\r   To add or delete a taxing authority, select it from the appropriate list. NOTE: Only one authority can be added or removed at this time. To add more than one authority, save the entry and then edit it to add more. \r   If freight is taxable, selct the Yes radio box. \r   Press the Save icon to commit the entry to the database. \r \r Editing a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the sales tax rate to edit. A popup will appear with a form filled out with the current tax rate information.\r   Edit the short name or description as necessary.\r   To add or delete a taxing authority, select it from the appropriate list. NOTE: Only one authority can be added or removed at this time. To add more than one authority, save the entry and then edit it to add or remove another authority. \r   If freight is taxable, selct the Yes radio box. \r   Press the Save icon to commit the change to the database.\r \r Deleting a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the sales tax rate to delete. A confirmation popup will appear to verfiy the delete request.\r   Press OK to remove the sales tax rate from the database.\r \r Related Links\r Sales Tax Overview\r   Sales Tax Authorities'),(267,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/SalesTaxHome.html','07.08.03','Setup - Sales Tax','Setup - Sales Tax\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax\r PhreeBooks has a multilevel sales tax rate calculator built in. Sales tax is comprised of Tax Authorities and Tax Rates. Tax authorities are defined as the agencies that collect the tax and tax rates are a collection of one or more authorities. \r Phreebooks inventory items can be individually set as taxable or non-taxable. When an order is placed, one sales tax rate is applied to the entire order, but will not be calculated if the inventory item is tagged as non-taxable. For example, if a labor item is included in the invoice and is not taxable, it shouldbe flagged as non-taxable in the inventory database and thus will not be included in the sales tax calculation for the invoice. \r See the links below for detailed information on setting up, managing and removing sales tax authorities and rates. \r Related Links \r Sales Tax Authorities\r Sales Tax Rates'),(268,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/02-Currencies/CurrenciesHome.html','07.08.02','Setup - Currencies','Setup - Currencies     Setup - Currencies PhreeBooks is designed to handle multiple currencies. the US Dollar is the default currency shipped with the standard release. Updating the exchange rate  Exchange rates can be updated through two exchange servers, oanda and xe. Oanda is the primary server and xe is the backup server should oanda be down.     Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Update Exchange Rate icon, . The exchange rat servers will be queried and the rates updated.   Adding a Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the New icon and a popup will appear.   Select the Title of the currency, i.e. US Dollar, Euro, Yen, etc.    Enter the ISO code for the currency, USD, EUR, etc.    Enter the symbol to use to the left and/or right, $ for USD, &euro; for EUR, etc.    Enter the symbol to use for the thousands place and decimal places.   Enter the current exchange rate relative to the default currency. Leave the value blank if it will be updated when the exchange rate is updated.   If this is to be the default currency, check the Set as Default box.    Press the Save icon to save the entry into the database.   Press the Update Exchange Rate icon to refresh the current exchange rate with the exchange rate servers.   Changing the Default Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Edit icon next to the currency to set as default and a popup will appear.   Check the Set as Default box.    Press the Save icon to save the entry into the database.  Deleteing a Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Delete icon next to the currency to delete and a confirmation popup will appear.   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the currency will be removed from the database.   Related Links &nbsp;'),(269,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/07-Users/UserHome.html','07.08.07','Setup - Users','Setup - Users     Setup - Users PhreeBooks user accounts allow for individualized access to the PhreBooks modules. User accounts are used in the audit log, setting access permissions, and permissions for reports.  When the PhreeBooks systems is installed, a single administrator account is added given full permission to access all of the PhreeBooks functionality. New users can be added and thier access can be controlled to modules that they are given permission to access. If No Access is given to a function, the option will not appear in their menu when they log in.  NOTE: When adding new modules, permissions have not been established and the modules will not be visible. Each user account will need to be edited and the appropriate permission added to access the module. Adding a User Account     Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Add icon. A new screen will appear with a form to fill out for the new user.   Enter a username, email address, and password for the new user.   Set the permissions for the user. A tab will appear for each main heading. the permissions are initially set for no access for all modules. Select the permission levels for each module in each tab.   Press the Save icon to create the user account.  Editing a User Account    Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Edit icon next to the user to edit. A new screen will appear with a form  fill out for the new user.   Edit any user information and security permissions as necesary. If the password will no be changed, leave the password fields blank and no changes will be made to the current password in the database.    Press the Save icon to update the user account.  Deleting a User Account    Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Delete icon next to the user to delete. A popup will appear to confirm the selection.    Press OK to confirm the selection and the user account will be removed from the database.  Related Links &nbsp;'),(270,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/08-Setup/04-Branches/BranchesHome.html','07.08.04','Setup - Company Branches','Setup - Company Branches     Setup - Company Branches &nbsp;'),(271,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/EmployeesHome.html','07.07','Employees','Employees - Homepage \r \r \r Employees - Homepage\r Employees are the people you pay wages to within your company. \r Adding an employee\r Changing or updating employee information\r Deleting an employee \r \r &nbsp;'),(272,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/01-Maintenance/MaintenanceHome.html','07.07.01','Employees - Maintenance','Employees - Maintenance     Employees - Maintenance Employees are the people you pay wages to within your company.  Adding an employee Changing or Updating  Employee Information  Deleting an Employee'),(273,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/01-Maintenance/02-EditEmployee.html','07.07.01.02','Editing Employees','Editing Employees\r \r \r \r \r Editing Employees\r To edit a employee record:\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Maintain Employees page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the employee to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the employee.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the employee.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Employees page. \r \r Related Topics\r Employees\r Adding a new employee account\r  Deleting an employee account\r Setting up a employee credit limit\r Checking employee balances \r &nbsp;\r &nbsp;'),(274,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/01-Maintenance/03-DeleteEmployee.html','07.07.01.03','Deleting Employees','Deleting Employees\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting Employees\r NOTE: Employees cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a employee record:\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Maintain Employees page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the employee to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the employee.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Employees page. \r \r Related Topics\r Employees\r Adding a new employee account\r  Deleting an employee account \r Checking employee balances \r &nbsp;\r &nbsp;'),(275,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/01-Maintenance/01-NewEmployee.html','07.07.01.01','Entering an Employee','Entering an Employee\r \r \r \r \r Entering an Employee\r Employee accounts include any personnel on your payroll. \r To create a new account:\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;New Employee or Select the New icon form the Employees-&gt;Maintain Employees page.\r    Enter an unique Employee ID. The Employee ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this employee form all other customers. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact  and Main Mailing address information. Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the employee type.\r   Enter the department the employee is part of. \r   Enter the employees Government ID number (Social Security Number). \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Employees page. \r \r Related Topics\r Employees\r Changing or updating an employee information\r  Deleting an employee account\r Departments\r Adding a department\r   Editing a department\r   Deleting a department\r \r &nbsp;'),(276,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/02-Payroll/PayrollHome.html','07.07.02','Employees - Payroll','Employees - Payroll     Employees - Payroll &nbsp;'),(277,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/04-Departments/DepartmentsHome.html','07.07.04','Employees - Departments','Employees - Departments\r \r \r \r \r Employees - Departments\r PhreeBooks allows employees to be grouped by departments. Departments are organized in a hierarchical manner. Departments are used for reporting and to help set roles and identify your companies structure.\r Adding a Department \r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Departments.\r   Press the New icon. A popup will appear to enter the information. \r   Enter the Department ID. (short description of the department, department number, etc.)\r   Enter a description of the department, formal name, etc.\r     If this department is a subordinate to another department, Select the Yes button and choose the department from the drop down menu.\r   Select the type of department this department is a part of. \r   Enter the name of the department type and press Save. \r \r Editing a Department\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Departments.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the department you wish to edit. A popup will appear with the current information fill in. \r   Make any necessary changes and  press Save to update the database.\r   \r Deleting a Department\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Departments.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the department you wish to delete. A popup will appear to confirm the deletion. \r   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the department will be removed from the database.\r \r Assigning an Employee to a Department\r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Maintain Employees\r    Press the Edit icon next to the employee you wish to assign to a department. \r   On the employee maintain screen, select the department to assign to this employee.\r   Press the Save icon to commit your changes and update the database.\r \r Related Topics\r Adding Employees\r   Editing Employees\r   Deleting Employees  \r   Adding Department Types\r \r &nbsp;'),(278,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/07-Employees/03-DeptTypes/DeptTypesHome.html','07.07.03','Employees - Department Types','Employees - Department Types\r \r \r \r \r Employees - Department Types\r PhreeBooks allows departments to be grouped by department types. Departments are organized in a hierarchical manner. Departments are used for reporting and to help set roles and identify your companies structure.\r Adding a Department Type \r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Department Types.\r   Press the New icon.\r   Enter the name of the department type and press Save.  \r \r Editing a Department Type \r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Department Types.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the department type to edit. A popup window will appear with the department type listed. \r   Make any necessary changes and press Save. the popup will close and the changes will be saved. \r \r Deleting a Department Type \r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Department Types.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the department type to delete. A confirmation window will appear to confirm the request. \r   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the department type will be removed from the database.\r \r Assigning an Department to a Department Type \r \r   Select Employees-&gt;Departments.\r   Press the edit icon next to the department to assign. A popup window will appear with the department information.\r   Select the department type to assign this department and press the Save icon. The department type will be assigned to the department and saved in the database. \r \r Related Topics\r Adding a Department\r   Editing a Department  \r   Deleting a Department\r &nbsp;'),(279,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/02-EditContact.html','07.03.02.02','Editing Customer Contacts','Editing a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Contact \r To edit a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the customer to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the customer.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact \r   Deleting a customer contact \r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),(280,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/ContactsHome.html','07.03.02','Customers - Customer Contacts','Customers - Customer Contacts\r \r \r \r \r Customers -  Contacts\r Customer contacts contain information about your customers of your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete customer contacts is similar to that for vendors within PhreeBooks. \r Customer Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for sales account and terms; customizable for each individual customer \r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individaul sales rep default assignment \r   Freee-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a new Customer\r   Updating customer information\r   Deleting a Customer\r Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r   Printing a sales order\r   Checking sales order status \r \r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing inventory from a sales order\r \r Point of Sale (POS)\r \r Other Customer Actions \r Checking customer balances \r   Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Receiving a payment from a customer\r   Issuing a credit memo\r &nbsp;'),(281,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/01-NewContact.html','07.03.02.01','Entering Customer Contacts','Entering a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Customer Contact \r Customer contacts include any outside organization that you sell goods or services to. Generally, they are organizations that you receive payments from. \r NOTE: Customer contacts may be created at time of sale by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Sales/Invoice, Receipt or Sales Order form. In this case, an unique contact ID must be entered and the contact will be created using the standard terms, default Sales GL account. No User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses will be created with the add/update feature. \r To create a new contact:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;New Customer or Select the New icon form the Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r    Enter an unique Customer ID. The Customer ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this customer form all other customers. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact  and Main Mailing (invoicing) Address information. Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default sales account. This is typically an accounts receivable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this customer. \r   Enter your account number with this customer. This number can be used for sales orders, invoices to reference their account to the customer.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the customer will be shipping to multiple locations, additional ship to addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the customer. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a customer by customer basis. \r   If the customer has additional remit to (invoicing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r   Updating a customer contact\r   Deleting a customer contact\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Sales/Invoice\r Selling items from a Sales Order \r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),(282,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/03-DeleteContact.html','07.03.02.03','Deleting Customer Contacts','Deleting a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Contact \r NOTE: Customers cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the customer to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact \r   Editing a customer contact \r Sales Orders\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),(283,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/04-PaymentTerms.html','07.03.02.04','Customer Payment Terms','Customer Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Customer Payment Terms\r Customer payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new customer contacts. Additionally, existing contacts with out terms defined (or \'Use Standard Terms\') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual customer terms may also be set up for customers whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific sales through the Sales Order/Invoice procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Customer Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default customer credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Customer Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers. \r   Search for the customer whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this customer.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current customer.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales/Invoice (or Sales Order, Customer Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact\r   Editing a customer contact\r Sales Orders\r  Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),(284,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/01-General/GeneralHome.html','07.03.01','Customers - General Information','Customers - General Information     Customers - General Information This section covers the activites realted to your customers. Accounts -  Sales Orders -  Sales Quotes -  Sales/Invoices -  Point Of Sale -  Credit Memos -  Customer  Status -'),(285,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/CustomerHome.html','07.03','Customers','Customers Home\r \r \r \r \r Customers Home\r Customers are your purchasers of products and services provided by your company.  They are used in PhreeBooks to represent people or companies that payments (receipts) are made from.  Generally, customers include anyone that you receive payments from.\r PhreeBooks uses a single database table to hold vendor and customer account information. \r Customer account features include:\r \r   Fields for main account address along with unlimited branch billing  and shipping addresses.\r   Default general ledger settings for receipts (sales) \r   2 main telephone numbers; 1 fax number, email and website field\r   Customer account number\r   Assign sales representatives to individual accounts\r   Government tax re-sale number field \r   Discount and Payment terms specific to an account\r \r Related Topics\r User and Security Settings\r Setting user access security\r Setting up sales representatives\r Customer Accounts\r Entering a customer account\r   Deleting a customer account\r   Editing a customer account\r   Setting default payment terms \r   Adding branch and shipping addresses\r \r General Ledger\r Adding a general ledger sales account\r Sales\r  Enter a customer quote \r   Enter a sales order \r   Enter an invoice\r   Receiving a payment\r   Enter a customer credit memo\r   Using point of sale (POS)\r Reports and Forms\r Standard customer reports\r   Standard customer forms\r &nbsp;'),(286,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/06-POS/POSHome.html','07.03.06','Customers - Point of Sale','Customers - Point of Sale     Customers - Point of Sale Point of sale is processed the same as a sale/invoice except payment is received at the time of invoice. In the Sales/Invoice window press the payment button after completing the invoice to post the invoice and open the payment receipts window to process the payment and print a receipt.'),(287,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/07-CreditMemo/CreditMemoHome.html','07.03.07','Customers - Credit Memos','Customers - Credit Memos\r \r \r \r \r Customers - Credit Memos\r Entering a credit memo\r    Deleting a credit memo\r    Editing a credit memo\r Printing a credit memo\r &nbsp;'),(288,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/07-CreditMemo/03-DeleteCrdMemo.html','07.03.07.03','Deleting a Customer Credit Memo','Deleting a Customer Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Credit Memo\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the invoice. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the invoice can be deleted. In this case, the invoice should be closed. See Closing a Credit Memo. Closing a invoice will remove all remaining \'quantity on invoice\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the credit memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be deleted and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will affect the income statement and balance sheet since a credit memo represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Credit Memos\r Entering a credit memo\r   Editing a credit memo\r Closing a credit memo'),(289,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/07-CreditMemo/02-EditCrdMemo.html','07.03.07.02','Editing a Customer Credit Memo','Editing a Customer Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Credit Memo\r Editing an invoice can be performed at any time.\r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Credit Memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be edited and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Enter any changes, as needed, to the credit memo. If any line items from the credit memo have been shipped, that particular line item cannot be deleted or the SKU changed.\r   Press the Save button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is re-posted in the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will  affect the income statement and balance sheet since a invoice represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r Adding a new customer account \r    Updating a customer account\r    Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r   Shipping an invoice\r Credit Memos \r Entering a credit memo\r   Deleting a credit memo'),(290,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/07-CreditMemo/01-EnterCrdMemo.html','07.03.07.01','Entering a Customer Credit Memo','Entering Customer Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Credit Memos\r Credit Memos are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a credit memo has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or credit memos can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Credit Memos do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Credit Memo form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this credit memo.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the credit memo Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Credit Memo Number - Enter the credit memo number. If left blank, the next credit memo number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the customers purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this credit memo and press Save to enter the terms into the credit memo form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the credit memo. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the credit memo form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the credit memo. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the credit memo will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a new Customer\r   Updating customer information\r   Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Receiving a credit memo\r Credit Memos\r Deleting a credit memo\r   Editing a credit memo\r Entering a credit memo\r Printing a credit memo'),(291,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/01-EnterQuote.html','07.03.04.01','Entering Customer Request for Quote','Entering Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Request for Quote\r Request for Quote are used to enter purchase from a customer. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Request for Quotes do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the request for quote form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this request for quote.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the request for quote Post Date and expected Receipt Date. Popup calendars are provided to help with the selection.\r    request for quote Number - Enter the request for quote number. If left blank, the next sequential request for quote number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the your purchase reference   number, store id and purchase representative. The default accounts payable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this request for quote and press Save to enter the terms into the request for quote form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the request for quote. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the request for quote form. Enter the quantity requested. The item cost value assigned to the sku will be placed in the price field and the line total will be calculated. \r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the request for quote. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the request for quote number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the request for quote will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a customer account\r    Editing a customer account\r    Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Request for Quotes\r  Deleting a request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r Printing a request for quote'),(292,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/QuotesHome.html','07.03.04','Customers - Quotes','Customers - Quotes\r \r \r Customers - Quotes\r Customer Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Edit a customer request for quote \r Delete a customer request for quote \r &nbsp;'),(293,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/02-EditQuote.html','07.03.04.02','Deleting Customer Request for Quote','Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Editing a Customer Request for Quote\r Customer sales  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Delete a customer request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r &nbsp;'),(294,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/03-DeleteQuote.html','07.03.04.03','Deleting Customer Request for Quote','Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r Purchase  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Edit a customer request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r &nbsp;'),(295,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/08-Status/StatusHome.html','07.03.08','Customers - Status','Customers - Status     Customers - Status Customer status.'),(296,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/02-EditSO.html','07.03.03.02','Editing a Customer Sales Orders','Editing a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Sales Order\r Sales  orders can only be edited if no items have been received from the sales order. If any items have been received, the corresponding sales/receipt must be removed before the sales order can be edited. In this case, the sales order should be closed. See Closing a Sales Order. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be edited and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired sales order. \r   \r   Make any necessary changes. Item rows may not be changed if some or all have been received.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes.\r \r When a sales order is saves, the journal entry is re-posted to the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sales (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r Entering a new customer \r     Editing a customer contact \r     Deleting a customer contact \r     Setting customer payment\r     Payment terms and credit limits \r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),(297,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/05-CloseSO.html','07.03.03.05','Closing Sales Orders','Closing a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r Closing a Customer Sales Order\r Sales  orders can  be closed for several reasons. They may be closed directly from the Edit SO screen by selecting the close button. Closed SOs will not affect the inventory levels or appear in any inventory stock level calculations. SOs may also be closed by PhreeBooks if all the items have been shipped through the Sales/invoice screen. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining \'quantity on  sales order\' quantities from inventory identified in the sales order being closed that have not been shipped. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be closed and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired sales order. \r   \r   Check the Close selection box.\r   Press the Save button.\r \r When a sales order is closed, the  quantity on  sales order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sales (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r     Editing a sales order\r     Deleting a sales order\r Checking sales order status (Sales Order Manager) \r &nbsp;'),(298,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/01-EnterSO.html','07.03.03.01','Entering Sales Orders','Entering Customer Sales Orders\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Sales Orders\r Sales orders are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a sales order has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or invoices can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Sales orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Sales Order form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this sales order.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the sales order Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Sales Order Number - Enter the sales order number. If left blank, the next sales order number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the customers purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this sales order and press Save to enter the terms into the sales order form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the sales order. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the sales order form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the sales order. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the sales order will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers Accounts\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Updating a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r  Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Shipping a sales order\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r  Closing a sales order\r Printing a sales order\r Printing a pick list/packing list\r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing a sales order'),(299,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/03-DeleteSO.html','07.03.03.03','Deleting Sales Orders','Deleting a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Sales Order\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the sales order. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the sales order can be deleted. In this case, the sales order should be closed. See Closing a Sales Order. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining \'quantity on sales order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales order for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r     \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a Sales Order is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on sales order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r     Closing a sales order'),(300,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/SOHome.html','07.03.03','Sales Orders - Overview','Entering Customer Sales Orders\r \r \r \r \r  Customer Sales Orders\r Sales orders are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a sales order has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or invoices can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Sales orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r Partial shipments are possible from a single sales order.\r NOTE: Sales orders are not required if you operate in a point-of-sale type sales system. In this case entering the sales directly as sales/invoice or point-of-sale is all that is required. \r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Updating a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r  Checking customer balances \r \r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Printing a pick list/packing list\r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing a sales order\r Shipping\r Shipping a sales order'),(301,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/04-SOManager.html','07.03.03.04','Sales Order Manager','Sales Order Manager\r \r \r \r Sales Order Manager\r The sales order manager is a powerful tool to manage your companies sales orders. From this function, you can  enter and review expected shipment dates, print copies of the sales order, or edit the sales order. The sales order manager default to the current period but a search field and period selection pull down are provided to help locate SOs anywhere in the system.\r Sales Order Manager Features:\r \r   Easily view sales orders and determine open/closed status and expected shipment dates \r   Powerful search capabilities to find or filter results\r   Ability to print SOs without opening them up or re-posting\r   Ability to set expected shipment dates so you know when shipments are expected, helps manage inventory\r   Ability to open for edit the sales order and review additional details\r   Ability to invoice a sales order \r \r Viewing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager\r   Locate the sales order to view and press the icon labeled Edit.\r   The Sales Order screen will load and the form will be filled in with the information of the selected SO.\r   From here, the sales order may be edited, deleted, closed or reviewed.\r \r Printing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager\r   Locate the sales order to print and press the icon labeled Print.\r   The reportwriter form display screen will appear listing the available forms to print.\r   Select the form to print, the delivery method, and press the PDF icon to generate the form. \r \r Invoicing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager \r   Locate the sales order to invoice and press the button labeled Invoice.\r   The Sales/Invoice screen will load and the remaining items from the selected SO will be shown.\r   Enter in the quantities to ship for each line item.\r    Make any other changes as necessary; such as the customers purchase order number shipment details, etc.\r   Press the Save icon to save the invoice or the receipt icon to receive payment form the customer.\r \r Changing Delivery Dates for a Sales Order\r When a sales order is placed, the expected shipment date is set to the post date. The estimated shipment dates may be modified here to reflect the current estimated shipment dates for each line item on the SO. the shipment dates field is useful to identify when items are expected for filling back-orders and notifications of expected arrivals of inventory items.\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager \r   Locate the sales order to adjust or view the expected shipment dates and press the button labeled \'Delivery Dates\'.\r   A popup will appear listing each line item from the SO, the quantity ordered and the description. The currently expected shipment date will also be displayed.\r   If necessary, enter a new shipment date for each item on the SO. A popup calendar is provided to help locate dates. If no change is necessary, leave the date field blank to retain the current shipment date. \r   After updating all affected shipment dates, press the Save icon the save the charges and return to the Sales Order Manager window. \r \r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r Adding a new customer account \r    Updating a customer account\r    Deleting a customer account\r   Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r     Editing a sales order\r     Deleting a sales order\r     Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Open sales order report'),(302,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/02-EditAccount.html','07.03.02.02','Editing Customer Account','Editing a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Account \r To edit a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the customer to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the customer.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Deleting a customer account \r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),(303,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/01-NewAccount.html','07.03.02.01','Entering Customer Accounts','Entering a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Customer Account \r Customer accounts include any outside organization that you sell goods or services to. Generally, they are organizations that you receive payments from. \r NOTE: Customer accounts may be created at time of sale by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Sales/Invoice, Receipt or Sales Order form. In this case, an unique account ID must be entered and the account will be created using the standard terms, default Sales GL account. No User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses will be created with the add/update feature. \r To create a new account:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;New Customer or Select the New icon form the Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r    Enter an unique Customer ID. The Customer ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this customer form all other customers. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact and Main Mailing (invoicing) Address information.  Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default sales account. This is typically an accounts receivable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this customer. \r   Enter your account number with this customer. This number can be used for sales orders, invoices to reference their account to the customer.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the customer will be shipping to multiple locations, additional ship to addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the customer. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a customer by customer basis. \r   If the customer has additional remit to (invoicing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r   Updating a customer account\r   Deleting a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Sales/Invoice\r Selling items from a Sales Order \r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),(304,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/03-DeleteAccount.html','07.03.02.03','Deleting Customer Account','Deleting a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Account \r NOTE: Customers cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the customer to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Editing a customer account \r Sales Orders\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),(305,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/AccountsHome.html','07.03.02','Customers - Customer Accountss','Customers - Customer Accounts\r \r \r \r \r Customers -  Accounts\r Customer accounts contain information about your customers of your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete customer account is similar to that for vendors within PhreeBooks. \r Customer Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for sales account and terms; customizable for each individual customer \r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individual sales rep default assignment \r   Free-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a new Customer\r   Updating customer information\r   Deleting a Customer\r Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r   Printing a sales order\r   Checking sales order status \r \r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing inventory from a sales order\r Using point of sale (POS)\r Other Customer Actions \r Checking customer balances \r   Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Receiving a payment from a customer\r   Issuing a credit memo\r &nbsp;'),(306,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/04-PaymentTerms.html','07.03.02.04','Customer Payment Terms','Customer Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Customer Payment Terms\r Customer payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new customer account.  Additionally, existing accounts with out terms defined (or \'Use Standard Terms\') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual customer terms may also be set up for customers whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific sales through the Sales Order/Invoice procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Customer Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default customer credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Customer Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers. \r   Search for the customer whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this customer.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current customer.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales/Invoice (or Sales Order, Customer Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account\r   Editing a customer account\r Sales Orders\r  Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),(307,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/05-Invoices/04-InvoiceManager.html','07.03.05.04','Invoice Manager','Invoice Manager\r \r \r \r \r Invoice Manager\r &nbsp;\r Related Topics\r Invoices\r Entering an invoice\r Closing an invoice'),(308,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/05-Invoices/02-EditInv.html','07.03.05.02','Editing an Invoice','Editing a Customer Invoice\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Invoice\r Editing an invoice can be performed at any time.\r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Invoices. The Invoice form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the invoice for the current period. Select the invoice to be edited and the invoice form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired invoice. \r   \r   Enter any changes, as needed, to the invoice. If any line items form the invoice hve been shipped, that particular line item cannot be deleted or the SKU changed.\r   Press the Save button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an invoice is edited, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will  affect the income statement and balance sheet since an invoice represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account \r     Updating a customer account\r     Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r   Shipping an invoice\r Invoices\r Entering an invoice\r    Deleting an invoice'),(309,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/05-Invoices/InvoicesHome.html','07.03.05','Customers - Invoices','Customers - Invoices\r \r \r \r \r Customers - Sales/Invoices\r Customer sales/invoices are represented as inventory items and services  offered or sold through your company to your customers. Sales affect the financial picture of your company. All sales records are maintained in the sales/invoice journal. \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering  a sales order\r   Invoicing inventory sold through a sales order\r   Shipping inventory sold through a sales order\r   Selling directly to customers\r Using point of sale (POS)\r   Editing an invoice\r   Deleting an invoice\r Checking customer balances \r Inventory\r Adding inventory items\r Banking\r Receiving customer payments\r   Creating a bank deposit\r   Writing a check to a customer \r Reports\r Checking inventory balances\r   Customer history report'),(310,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/05-Invoices/01-EnterInv.html','07.03.05.01','Entering an Invoice','Entering Customer Sale/Invoice\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Invoice\r Sales orders are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a invoice has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or invoices can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Sales orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Invoices. The Invoice form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Invoice form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this invoice.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the invoice Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Invoice Number - Enter the invoice number. If left blank, the next invoice number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the customers purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this invoice and press Save to enter the terms into the invoice form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the invoice. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the invoice form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the invoice. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the invoice will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Adding a new customer account \r   Updating a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Shipping an invoice\r Sales/Invoice\r Deleting an invoice\r Editing an invoice\r Printing an invoice\r Printing an pick list/packing list\r Banking\r Receiving customer payments\r Creating a bank deposit\r Writing a check to a customer'),(311,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/03-Customers/05-Invoices/03-DeleteInv.html','07.03.05.03','Deleting an Invoice','Deleting a Customer Invoice\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Invoice\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the invoice. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the invoice can be deleted. In this case, the invoice should be closed. See Closing a Invoice. Closing a invoice will remove all remaining \'quantity on invoice\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Invoices. The Invoice form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the invoice for the current period. Select the invoice to be deleted and the invoice form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r     \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a Invoice is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on invoice values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a invoice represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Invoices\r Entering an invoice\r Closing an invoice'),(312,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/InventoryHome.html','07.04','Inventory','Inventory Home\r \r \r \r \r Inventory\r PhreeBooks uses inventory to represent all items, activities, and services your company offers to its customers. \r Inventory types include:\r Stock - Represents items that are stocked by your company. This includes items that are purchased and re-sold by your company without any value-added provided by your company. Retail type companies typically use stock type items. Stock item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Master-Stock - Master-stock items are items that contain attributes associated with the item. For example, a shirt item would have the attributes size and color associated with each item. Phreebooks will assign a unique item id to each variation to track inventory activity of each size/color item but retain the link to the master stock item for reporting activity. Master-stock item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Serialized - Serialized items are items that are assembled and sold  by an unique serial number. Serialized item movement and cost are tracked in the general ledger. \r Assemblies - Item assemblies consist of one or more inventory items grouped together and sold as an individual item. This inventory type can also be used to group items sold as packages. Assembly item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Non-stock - Non-stock items are physical items whose costs are not tracked in the general ledger. They may include supplies, packaging material, assembly materials, etc. \r Labor - Labor items are associated with employee chargeable time. Labor may be applied to either internal work order activities as well as labor charges to customer for services performed. Labor is typically charged by a time unit (hourly, daily, etc).\r Service - Service items are items that typically represent a fixed charged for a service. For example, a packaging charge or handling would be a service. Service costs are tracked in the general ledger. \r Charge - A charge item would be a fixed price charge for materials and/or services. Shop supplies and disposal fees would be examples of charges. Charge item costs are tracked in the general ledger. \r Activity - \r Description - This is a text only item used to communicate information. No cost or activity is tracked in the general ledger. The description item would be typically used for standard statements included with purchase orders, sales orders, etc. \r Inventory Categories\r Phreebooks uses system and company categories to organize inventory characteristics. A default tab for system required fields cannot be edited or deleted. A second tab will be displayed for assembly type inventory items. Additional tabs may be added by the company to help further define the characteristics of their inventory items. For example, additional tabs may be added to include product dimensions, shipping properties, application descriptions, etc. \r Inventory Fields\r PhreeBooks allows additional fields to be entered to the inventory database table. This allows customized inventory characteristics to be added to fit your companies needs. Inventory field types include text, HTML, hyperlinks, image paths, inventory links, integers and floating point numbers, dates and times, drop-down menus radio buttons and checkboxes. Refer to the section on inventory fields for more information. \r Related Topics\r User and Security Settings\r Setting user access security\r Inventory Activities \r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Delete inventory items\r     Entering an inventory assembly\r Inventory Categories\r  Add inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Fields \r Adding an inventory field\r    Editing and inventory field\r    Deleting an inventory field\r  General Ledger\r Setting up default inventory accounts \r   Adding, editing and deleting general ledger accounts \r Importing/Exporting\r Building an import/export map\r   Importing/Exporting data\r Reports\r &nbsp;'),(313,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/01-Maintenance/03-CopyItem.html','07.04.01.03','Copying','Inventory - Copying Inventory\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Copying Inventory \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Edit/Maintain.\r   The inventory item list screen will appear initially sorted by SKU. To locate the item you wish to copy, navigate by clicking on the sorting selection in the table head or enter a search criteria in the search box and press the Enter key on your keyboard. \r   Once you locate the item to copy, click on the copy icon  and a popup window will appear requesting a SKU for the new item.\r   Enter the new SKU into the field and press OK to advance to the data entry screen. Most of the fields from the source item will be copied to the new item and will be shown on the form. Certain system items, such as quantity on hand, quantity on order, quantity on sales order will not be copied over and these fields will be initially set to zero. \r     \r     Depending on the inventory type and number of categories defined, the tabs displayed on the data entry screen will vary. The first tab and will be the System tab. If the inventory type is an assembly, the second tab will show the Bill of Materials and is used to enter the sku\'s used to make up the assembly. The remaining tabs are user defined and are ordered as defined in the inventory categories set up menu. \r   \r   Enter/change the information for the newly copied item. Use the tabs to select each category type and enter fields for that particular category.\r     \r     Note: Some fields may not be editable once certain journal entries have been made. For example, the cost method will be locked out once that item has been used in for a journal activity. Other fields are system maintained and cannot be changed. These fields are either read only or disabled and cannot be changed on the form. \r   \r   When all desired fields have been entered, press Update to save your information and return to the inventory edit/maintain window.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r   Adding inventory items\r   Editing inventory items \r   Deleting inventory items \r   Inventory adjustments\r   Entering an inventory assembly\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field \r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r   Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r   Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Activities \r Using the price manager\r   Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r   Synchronizing with other applications\r Reports\r Inventory item list\r   Inventory assembly list \r   Inventory adjustment journal\r   Inventory assembly journal'),(314,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/01-Maintenance/MaintenanceHome.html','07.04.01','Maintenance','Inventory - Maintenance\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Maintenance\r Inventory items represent the goods and services produced, bought, contracted or consumed by your company. PhreeBooks offers several inventory types to help manage the various attributes of each item. Some inventory types are tracked in your companies stock (stock items, master-stock items, assemblies) while others are not. All but the documentation type affect your companies financial position.\r To better help organize your inventory items, PhreeBooks has a built in category and field tool. Attributes of inventory items can be added to category groups which can then be used in reports, forms, imported, exported or transfered to interface third party applications. For example, a category named packaging may be added to the inventory items and fields for package length, width, height and weight may be added to the category. \r HINT: Before creating inventory items, setting up inventory categories and fields is recommended. If the categories and fields  are set up prior to copying inventory items, the new fields will be copied when the item is copied saving the time to re-enter the data.\r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r   Adding inventory items\r   Editing inventory items\r   Copying inventory items\r   Deleting inventory items\r   Inventory adjustments\r   Entering an inventory assembly\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field \r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r   Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r   Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Activities \r Using the price manager  \r  Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r   Synchronizing with other applications'),(315,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/01-Maintenance/02-EditItem.html','07.04.01.02','Editing','Inventory - Editing Inventory\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Editing Inventory \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Edit/Maintain.\r   The inventory item list screen will appear initially sorted by SKU. To locate the item you wish to edit, navigate by clicking on the sorting selection in the table head or enter a search criteria in the search box and press the Enter key on your keyboard. \r   Once you locate the item to edit, click on the edit icon  to advance to the date entry screen. \r     \r     Depending on the inventory type and number of categories defined, the tabs displayed on the data entry screen will vary. The first tab and will be the System tab. If the inventory type is an assembly, the second tab will show the Bill of Materials and is used to enter the skus used to make up the assembly. The remaining tabs are user defined and are ordered as defined in the inventory categories set up menu. \r   \r   Enter the information for the item. Use the tabs to select each category type and enter fields for that particular category.\r     \r     Note: Some fields may not be editable once certain journal entries have been made. For example, the cost method will be locked out once that item has been used in for a journal activity. Other fields are system maintained and cannot be changed. These fields are either read only or disabled and cannot be changed on the form. \r   \r   When all desired fields have been entered, press Update to save your information and return to the inventory edit/maintain window.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r   Adding inventory items\r   Copying inventory items\r   Deleting inventory items \r   Inventory adjustments\r   Entering an inventory assembly\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field \r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r   Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r   Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Activities \r Using the price manager\r   Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r   Synchronizing with other applications\r Reports\r Inventory item list\r   Inventory assembly list \r   Inventory adjustment journal\r   Inventory assembly journal'),(316,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/01-Maintenance/04-DeleteItem.html','07.04.01.04','Deleting','Inventory - Deleting Inventory\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Deleting Inventory \r Note: An inventory item cannot be deleted if there are journal entries posted with the item. If the user tries to delete an item that has been posted to the journal, an error will be displayed and the item will not be deleted. Once all journal entries related to this item have been removed, the item can be deleted. If this is not possible, consider marking the SKU as inactive.\r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Edit/Maintain.\r   The inventory item list screen will appear initially sorted by SKU. To locate the item you wish to edit, navigate by clicking on the sorting selection in the table head or enter a search criteria in the search box and press the Enter key on your keyboard. \r   Once you locate the item to edit, click on the delete icon   and a popup window will appear confirming the delete operation.\r   Click OK to confirm the delete operation and the item will be removed from the database.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r   Adding inventory items\r   Editing inventory items \r   Copying inventory items\r   Inventory adjustments\r   Entering an inventory assembly\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field \r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r   Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r   Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Activities \r Using the price manager\r   Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r   Synchronizing with other applications\r Reports\r Inventory item list\r   Inventory assembly list \r   Inventory adjustment journal\r   Inventory assembly journal'),(317,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/01-Maintenance/01-AddItem.html','07.04.01.01','Adding','Inventory - Adding Inventory\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Adding Inventory \r Inventory items represent the goods and services produced, bought, contracted or consumed by your company. PhreeBooks offers several inventory types to help manage the various attributes of each item. Some inventory types are tracked in your companies stock (stock items, master-stock items, assemblies) while others are not. All but the documentation type affect your companies financial position.\r To better help organize your inventory items, PhreeBooks has a built in category and field tool. Attributes of inventory items can be added to category groups which can then be used in reports, forms, imported, exported or transfered to interface third party applications. For example, a category named packaging may be added to the inventory items and fields for package length, width, height and weight may be added to the category. \r HINT: Before creating inventory items, setting up inventory categories and fields is recommended. If the categories and fields  are set up prior to copying inventory items, the new fields will be copied when the item is copied saving the time to re-enter the data.\r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Edit/Maintain.\r   At the bottom of the list click New.\r   Enter the SKU number for the item to create and select the inventory type form the pull down menu.\r     \r   NOTE: Duplicate SKUs are not permitted. If a SKU is entered that is already in the system, an error will be displayed and the new SKU will not be created.\r   \r    Press New to create the SKU and continue to the next screen.\r     \r   Depending on the inventory type and number of categories defined, the tabs displayed on the data entry screen will vary. The first tab and will be the System tab. If the inventory type is an assembly, the second tab will show the Bill of Materials and is used to enter the sku\'s used to make up the assembly. The remaining tabs are user defined and are ordered as defined in the inventory categories set up menu. \r   \r   Enter the information for the item. Use the tabs to select each category type and enter fields for that particular category.\r   When all desired fields have been entered, press Save to save your information and return to the inventory edit/maintain window. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r   Editing inventory items\r   Copying inventory items\r   Deleting inventory items\r   Inventory adjustments\r   Entering an inventory assembly\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field \r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r   Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r   Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Activities \r Using the price manager  \r   Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r   Synchronizing with other applications\r Reports\r Inventory item list\r   Inventory assembly list \r   Inventory adjustment journal\r   Inventory assembly journal'),(318,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/03-Assemblies/02-AssembliesDelete.html','07.04.03.02','Inventory Assemblies - Deleting','Inventory - Assemblies (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Assemblies (Delete)\r Delete inventory assembly procedure \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Assemblies.\r   Press the Open button to display the inventory assembly popup window. \r   Select the assembly to delete by clicking anywhere on the row of the adjustment.\r   Press the Delete button and  confirm you selection to un-post the transaction from the journal.\r \r &nbsp;\r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items \r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory assemblies   \r     Inventory assemblies - Edit\r     Inventory assemblies - Delete     \r     Adding an inventory field\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r     Adding Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r &nbsp;'),(319,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/03-Assemblies/01-AssembliesEdit.html','07.04.03.01','Inventory Assemblies - Editing','Inventory - Assemblies (Edit)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Assemblies (Edit) \r Edit inventory adjustment procedure \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Assemblies.\r   Press the Open button to display the inventory assemblies popup window. \r   Select the assembly to edit by clicking anywhere on the row of the assembly.\r   Change any fields as necessary. \r   Press Save to post the transaction to the journal. Note: Editing a journal entry first un-posts the original transaction and re-posts with the new data. Cost of good sold will be recalculated based on the post date of the edited adjustment.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory assemblies - Delete\r     Inventory assemblies   \r     Adding an inventory field\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r     Adding Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r &nbsp;'),(320,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/03-Assemblies/AssembliesHome.html','07.04.03','Assemblies','Inventory - Assemblies\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Assemblies\r Inventory assemblies are inventory items that are comprised of one or more other inventory items. When an inventory item is created, the inventory type is selected at the time the SKU is entered to identify the characteristics of the item. When the assembly type is selected the item is assumed to be made up with other items from the inventory database. In order to sell an assembly type item, it must be assembled in PhreeBooks to show stock on hand. Note that an assembled item may also be purchased directly in which case inventory will show stock but no assemblies were necessary. \r Inventory assembly procedure \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Assemblies.\r   Enter the SKU or a search criteria and press the open icon . Note: Only inventory items of type \'assembly\' will be displayed in the popup.\r   Select the SKU to assemble from the popup menu to fill in the item attributes (or if there is only one match, the popup window will close and fill in the necessary information). A list will be displayed of the required items and quantities needed to assemble the item and shortages will be displayed in red.\r   Enter a reference for this transaction (i.e. ADJ2007-05-12).\r   Enter the post date of the adjustment or use the popup calendar to select a post date. Today\'s date is loaded by default. \r   Enter the total number of units to assemble. After the number of units to assemble is entered, PhreeBooks calculates the number of required  items to build the requested amount and will warn if there are not enough pieces to build.\r   Press Save to post the transaction to the journal. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Inventory assemblies - Edit\r     Inventory assemblies - Delete\r     Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments - Adding \r     Adding an inventory field\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r     Adding Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r &nbsp;'),(321,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/02-Adjustments/01-AdjustmentEdit.html','07.04.02.01','Inventory Adjustments - Editing','Inventory - Adjustments (Edit)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Adjustments (Edit) \r Edit inventory adjustment procedure \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Adjustments.\r   Press the Open button to display the inventory adjustment popup window. \r   Select the adjustment to edit by clicking anywhere on the row of the adjustment.\r   Change any fields as necessary. \r   Press Save to post the transaction to the journal. Note: Editing a journal entry first un-posts the original transaction and re-posts with the new data. Cost of good sold will be recalculated based on the post date of the edited adjustment. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r     Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items \r     Inventory adjustment\r     Deleting an inventory adjustment\r     \r   Inventory assemblies\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field\r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory category \r   Editing an inventory category \r Deleting an inventory category\r &nbsp;'),(322,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/02-Adjustments/AdjustmentsHome.html','07.04.02','Adjustments','Inventory - Adjustments\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Adjustments\r Inventory adjustments are necessary when your physical inventory stock  counts do not match the calculated count within PhreeBooks. An inventory adjustment will be necessary to synchronize PhreeBooks with physical inventory. The two possible adjustments are increase in inventory (less physical inventory on hand than expected) and reduce inventory (more physical inventory on hand than expected). \r Inventory adjustment procedure \r  Inventory shortages can occur form many ways. Pilferage, damage, loss are a few. The stock counts within PhreeBooks will need to be adjusted to match the actual stock on hand. \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Adjustments.\r   Enter the SKU or a search criteria and press the open icon  . \r   Select the SKU to adjust from the popup menu to fill in the item attributes (or if there is only one match, the popup window will close and fill in the necessary information).\r   Enter a reference for this transaction (i.e. ADJ2007-05-12).\r   Enter the post date of the adjustment or use the popup calendar to select a post date. Today\'s date is loaded by default. \r   Select the GL account popup icon  and select the account to apply the adjustment. \r   Enter the total cost of the adjustment. This value only applies to increases in inventory. For inventory decreases, the cost field is ignored and the cost is calculated by PhreeBooks using the items cost method and historical purchase prices.\r   Enter the adjustment quantity.\r   Enter a reason for adjustment. (i.e. damaged, expired, etc.) \r   Press Save to post the transaction to the journal. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r     Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items\r     Edit an inventory adjustment\r     Deleting an inventory adjustment\r     Inventory assemblies\r     Adding an inventory field\r     Editing an inventory field \r     Deleting an inventory field\r     Adding an inventory field tab (category)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category)\r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r &nbsp;'),(323,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/02-Adjustments/02-AdjustmentDelete.html','07.04.02.02','Inventory Adjustments - Deleting','Inventory - Adjustments (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Adjustments (Delete) \r Delete inventory adjustment procedure \r \r   From the main menu, select Inventory-&gt;Adjustments.\r   Press the Open button to display the inventory adjustment popup window. \r   Select the adjustment to delete by clicking anywhere on the row of the adjustment.\r   Press the Delete button and confirm you selection to un-post the transaction from the journal.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Setting inventory default accounts\r     Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Deleting inventory items \r     Inventory adjustments\r     Edit an inventory adjustment\r      \r   Inventory assemblies\r   Adding an inventory field\r   Editing an inventory field\r   Deleting an inventory field\r   Adding an inventory category \r   Editing an inventory category \r Deleting an inventory category\r &nbsp;'),(324,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/FieldsHome.html','07.04.05','Custom Fields','Inventory - Custom Fields\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields\r PhreeBooks has a built in feature to expand inventory fields (attributes) to allow for further refinement of your inventory items. To help organize these expanded fields, added inventory fields are organized into categories. These categories become the tab headings when maintaining your inventory items. The mandatory inventory fields are, by default, put into the \'System\' category (tab). If the inventory type is an assembly, a second tab name \'Bill of Materials\' is also added. At least one category must be added before inventory fields can be entered. As many fields can be added to a category as are needed. \r Adding an Inventory Field\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Press the New button.\r   Enter a short name for the inventory field name, 10 characters or less, no spaces. This field must be compatible with the database naming convention. (mysql, etc.) \r   Enter a description. This is the field that will generally be used when maintaining inventory.\r   Select the category to place this field into. This will determine what tab heading the field will appear when inventory items are edited.\r   Enter the field type and properties. On some fields, default properties may be entered to pre-define the field when a new item is entered. \r   Press New to add the new inventory field.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Delete inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Editing an inventory field \r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(325,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/02-FieldsDelete.html','07.04.05.02','Deleting','Inventory - Custom Fields (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields (Delete)\r WARNING: Deleting a inventory custom field will delete all inventory information stored in the targeted field. This action is not reversible. \r Deleting an Inventory Custom Field\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Press the Delete button to delete and a confirmation will appear.\r   Press the Delete button on the confirmation to delete the custom field.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(326,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/01-FieldsEdit.html','07.04.05.01','Editing','Inventory - Custom Fields (Edit)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields (Edit)\r Editing a Custom Inventory Field \r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Edit the custom inventory fields. \r   Press Update to save your changes.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Adding an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(327,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/04-Tabs/02-TabsDelete.html','07.04.04.02','Inventory Tabs - Deleting','Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Delete)\r WARNING: Deleting a tab will also delete all inventory fields that are part of that tab. To keep the fields, edit each inventory field and reassign them to a valid tab before deleting.\r Deleting an Inventory tab (category)\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Field Tabs.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Edit the inventory tab fields. \r   Press the Delete button to delete and a confirmation will appear.\r   Press the Delete button on the confirmation to delete the tab.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory tab (category) \r     Inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(328,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/04-Tabs/01-TabsEdit.html','07.04.04.01','Inventory Tabs - Editing','Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Edit)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Edit)\r Editing an Inventory Tab (Category)\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Field Tabs.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Edit the inventory tab fields. \r   Press Update to save your changes. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory tabs (categories)\r     Deleting an inventory tab (category)\r     Inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(329,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/04-Inventory/04-Tabs/TabsHome.html','07.04.04','Inventory Tabs','Inventory - Tabs (Categories)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Tabs (Categories)\r PhreeBooks has a built in feature to expand inventory attributes (fields) to allow for further refinement of your inventory items.  To help organize these expanded fields, added inventory fields are organized into categories. These categories become the tab headings when maintaining your inventory items. The mandatory inventory fields are, by default, put into the \'System\' tab. If the inventory type is an assembly, a second tab name \'Bill of Materials\' is also added. At least one tab must be added before inventory fields can be entered.\r Adding an Inventory Tab (Category)\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Field Tabs.\r   Press the New button.\r   Enter a short name for the inventory tab, 10 characters or less, no spaces.\r   Enter the sort position. This will determine the display order of the tabs when maintaining inventory items.\r   Enter a tab description. This field will show up below the tab to describe the contents of the tab. \r   Press Insert to add the new tab. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Editing an inventory tab (category)\r     Deleting an inventory tab (category)\r     Add inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),(330,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/06-GenLedger/03-Utilities/UtilitiesHome.html','07.06.03','General Journal - Utilities','General Journal - Utilities     General Journal - Utilities General Journal utilities provide administrative functions such as fiscal year setup, defining the current accounting period, setting up beginning balances and purging the database tables. Security should be restricted to the general journal utilities since significant damage to the company data can be had here.  General Journal Utilities include: Accounting period change - Sets the current accounting period to a specified period. typically, this will need to be changed at the start of each accounting period as defined in the fiscal year. Fiscal Year setup, addition and change - the first fiscal year is set up through the setup script. This script allows for changes to any fiscal year and also generates the next fiscal year.  NOTE: For performance reasons, it is best not to generate the next fiscal year until it is necessary. Every journal entry that affects the financial statement propagates through the remaining periods from the post date to the last period defined in the database. This results in extra queries to the database and slows down each posting. NOTE: Once an entry has been entered for a period, the fiscal year for that period and any earlier periods will be locked and cannot be deleted or changed. Beginning Balances - This utility assists in transferring information from other accounting systems into PhreeBooks to retain continuity of financial reporting. Beginning balances set the trial balance accounts prior to period 1 (the default first accounting period). The beginning balance utility also allows for importing of inventory balances and valuation, customer accounts receivable, and vendor accounts payable. Database purge - THIS FUNCTION WILL DESTROY ALL THE JOURNAL ENTRIES AND BEGINNING BALANCES. It is included for test and evaluation purposes to quickly erase all journal entries and resets inventory balances to zero. It will not remove customers, vendors, employees or other set-up settings. &nbsp;'),(331,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/06-GenLedger/02-JournalEntries/JournalHome.html','07.06.02','General Journal - Journal Entries','General Journal - Journal Entries\r \r \r \r \r General Journal - Journal Entries\r Entries can be made directly into the general journal. However, most entries are handled in the background as through the system scripts.\r Notes:\r \r   The journal must be in balance before the entry can be posted.\r   The accounts selected must be a valid entry from the chart of accounts. \r \r Posting a general journal entry:\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Enter the general ledger account and a description of the entry. A popup window listing the chart of accounts. \r   Enter the amount of the journal entry.\r   Repeat steps 2-3 for all entries. Use the Add icon to add additional rows.\r   Verify the journal entries are in balance and press the Save icon to commit the changes.\r \r Editing a general journal entry: \r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Select the Open icon and a popup window will appear listing the entries for the current period. Select the entry to be edited or use the search/period selection to search for entries outside of the current period..\r   Edit any fields as necessary.\r   Verify the journal entries are in balance and press the Save icon to commit the changes. This action will first un-post the prior entry and re-post with the new values. \r \r Deleting a general journal entry:\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Select the Open icon and a popup window will appear listing the entries for the current period. Select the entry to be edited or use the search/period selection to search for entries outside of the current period..\r   Press the delete Icon and after confirmation, the journal entry will be un-posted and removed from the database.\r \r Related Links\r Chart of Accounts\r   Reports - Balance Sheet\r Reports - Income Statement \r &nbsp; \r &nbsp;'),(332,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/06-GenLedger/GLHome.html','07.06','General Ledger','General Ledger Home     General Ledger Home &nbsp;'),(333,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/06-GenLedger/01-ChartOfAccounts/ChartHome.html','07.06.01','General Journal - Chart of Accounts','General Journal - Chart of Accounts\r \r \r \r \r General Journal - Chart of Accounts\r The chart of accounts is the key to a successful accounting application. Phreebooks allow for accounts name that include characters as well as numbers. It also allows for sub-accounts to be used later in roll-up reporting. If you are not sure how to set up your chart of accounts, refer to your accountant or use one of the supplied chart of accounts during the set-up script.\r Notes: \r \r   Exactly one account of type \'Retained Earnings\' may be part of the chart of accounts.\r   Accounts cannot be deleted if they have been used in a journal entry.\r   Accounts should be checked as inactive if they are no longer used but have past journal entries against it.\r \r Adding a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Chart of Accounts.\r   Click on the New icon and a popup will appear.\r   Enter the GL account number (0-9 and a-z are allowed).\r   Enter the description, and subaccount information as necessary.\r   Enter the Account Type. This classifies the account and how entries are treated in the general journal.\r   Press Save to create the account and close the window.\r \r Deleting a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Chart of Accounts.\r   Click the Delete icon next to the account to be deleted.\r   Acknowledge the deletion and the account will be removed.\r     NOTE: if the account has journal entries in the database, the account cannot be deleted.\r \r Editing a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Ledger-Chart of Accounts.\r   Click the edit icon next to the account to be edited. \r   Make any changes and press Save to commit your changes and close the window.\r     NOTE: Account numbers cannot be changed if they have a journal entry posted against it.\r \r Related Links\r General Journal Entries\r   Reports - Balance Sheet\r   Reports - Income Statement\r &nbsp;'),(334,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/03-BankRegister/RegisterHome.html','07.05.03','Banking - Cash Register','Banking - Cash Register\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Cash Register \r PhreeBooks provides a view of the current status of your cash accounts. The register shows all deposits and withdrawals for a given accounting period, including future posted transactions.\r To View Your Cash Account\r \r   Select Banking -&gt; Bank Account Register.\r   The screen will display a beginning balance for the period and all transactions that were posted for the period. \r   To change cash accounts, select a new account from the GL Account pull down menu. \r \r Related Topics\r Reports\r Printing Deposit Slips \r Printing Bank Checks'),(335,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/01-Payments/PaymentsHome.html','07.05.01','Banking - Payments','Banking - Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Payments\r Bill Payments by Check - There are two ways to pay bills, individually or in bulk:\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r &nbsp;'),(336,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/01-Payments/01-SinglePayments.html','07.05.01.01','Banking - Single Payments','Banking - Single Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Single Payments\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other non-paper method to a single vendor. This method is best used when payment is desired to a single vendor as it allows for easier selection of the vendor of interest. Payments Ref Numbers cannot be duplicated in the system. \r To pay a bill to a single vendor - writing a check \r \r   From the menu click on Banking -&gt; Pay Bills.\r   Enter part of the vendor name to search for and press the open folder icon next to the vendor id field.\r   A popup will be displayed showing the vendors that match the entered search criteria. NOTE: Only the vendors that have an outstanding bill to be paid will be displayed. If the vendor is not listed, make sure there is an open invoice entered into PhreeBooks to pay.\r   Click anywhere on the vendor name to fill in the Payments form and close the popup.\r   All outstanding invoices from this vendor will be displayed, including any open vendor credit memos. Click on the Pay checkbox next to all the invoices you wish to pay. If the vendor payment terms have been set, any early payment discounts will be calculated. They may also be entered manually (note that the balance is calculated automatically if a discount is entered).\r   Enter the Payment Ref #, this is usually the check number to be printed.\r    Enter the check date, Reference, and account information as necessary. \r   Press the Print icon to generate the form. The forms of type banking:checks will be displayed. Check the radio button of the form to print, select the delivery method and press the PDF icon. \r   Print to the pre-printed checks on the printer.\r \r The Payment Ref Num will be automatically incremented.\r To pay a bill via EFT, credit card, and other non-check methods \r \r   Follow the procedure above, except enter an unique Payment Ref that identifies the payment. Select the correct account and post the payment by clicking the Save icon. To pay by credit card, select a short term liability account to post the payment to. \r \r NOTE: After paying with this method, the Payment Ref Num will auto-increment, probably to something non-desirable. It will need to be re-entered (back to the next check num) when the next run of bills are paid by checks to the next check number.\r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r   Paying Bills with credit cards \r   Reconciling cash accounts \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r &nbsp;'),(337,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/01-Payments/02-BulkPayments.html','07.05.01.02','Banking - Bulk Payments','Banking - Bulk Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Bulk Payments\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other non-paper method to one or more vendors. This method is preferred for paying vendor invoices to multiple vendors in a single operation. Payments Ref Numbers cannot be duplicated in the system but this procedure automatically increments the Payment Ref Numbers as each payment is generated. \r To pay a bill to multiple vendors - writing a checks \r \r   From the menu click on Banking -&gt; Select for Payment. A list of invoices that are due today will be displayed. Grayed out invoices may be shown and are an indication of invoices that are due but do not have an invoice number assigned to them.\r   Select a date form the Invoices Due By and Discounts Lost By calendar selections and press the Search icon. \r   A new list of invoices that are due (or discounts lost) will be displayed. Select all of the invoice to pay in this batch by checking the Pay checkboxes next tot he invoices to pay or press the Pay All icon to have PhreeBooks check all the boxes for you. Uncheck any invoices you don\'t want to pay. Discounts are automatically calculated and the balance of the cash account is calculated. \r   Enter the First Check Number, this is  the first check number to be printed. PhreeBooks will automatically increment the check number as the check for each vendor is generated. \r    Enter the check date,  and gl account information as necessary. \r   Press the Print icon to generate the form. The forms of type banking:checks will be displayed. Check the radio button of the form to print, select the delivery method and press the PDF icon. \r   PhreeBooks generates one check page for each vendor, combing all invoices from the same vendor into a single check. Print to the pre-printed checks on the printer (make sure the sequence is correct).\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r   Paying Bills with credit cards \r   Reconciling cash accounts \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r &nbsp;'),(338,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/02-Receipts/ReceiptsHome.html','07.05.02','Banking - Receipts','Banking - Receipts\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Receipts\r When a customer submits a payment for an outstanding invoice, the banking receipts function is used. \r Receiving Payment from a Customer\r \r   Select Banking-&gt;Customer Receipts .\r    Enter the Customer ID or press the open icon next to the Customer ID field. A popup will appear only displaying the customers with outstanding invoices. \r    Select the customer that you received a payment from. The popup window will close and fill in the list of outstanding invoices on the Pay Bills form.\r   Check the Pay box of the invoices you wish to pay. Adjust the discount as necessary. \r   Enter a Reference Number in the Reference field.\r   Enter the check number in the Deposit Ticket ID field.\r   Enter the date of the check (default is today).\r   Change the cash and discount accounts if necessary.\r   Select the Payment Method from the pull down menu. Fill in any necessary payment information.\r   Either Save or Print the payment. Saving is typically used for payments received where no receipt is necessary whereas printing is typically used for when a receipt is necessary (such as POS). The payment will be posted to the general ledger. \r \r Related Topics\r Voiding a Receipt \r   Editing a Receipt \r   Deleting a Receipt \r &nbsp;'),(339,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/02-Receipts/01-SingleReceipts.html','07.05.02.01','Banking - Customer Receipts','Banking - Customer Receipts\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Customer Receipts\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other  method from a single customer. Receipt Ref Numbers are automatically generated by the system (but can be over-ridden) to group deposits together. Deposit reference numbers can be duplicated in the system. \r Receiving Payment from a Customer\r \r   Select Banking-&gt;Customer Receipts .\r    Enter the Customer ID or press the open icon next to the Customer ID field. A popup will appear only displaying the customers with outstanding invoices. \r    Select the customer that you received a payment from. The popup window will close and fill in the list of outstanding invoices on the receipts form.\r   Check the Pay box of the invoices you receive money from. Adjust the discount as necessary. \r   Use the pre-selected deposit reference number of enter a reference number in the Deposit  ID field.\r   Enter the date of the deposit (default is today).\r   Change the cash and discount accounts if necessary.\r   Select the Deposit method from the pull down menu. Payment receipt methods are determined by the payment modules installed. Every payment module has their own set of fields to enter. Fill in any necessary payment information.\r   Either Save or Print the payment. Saving is typically used for payments received where no receipt is necessary whereas printing is typically used for when a receipt is necessary (such as POS). The payment will be posted to the general ledger. \r \r To pay a bill via EFT, credit card, and other non-check methods \r \r   Follow the procedure above, except enter an unique Payment Ref that identifies the payment. Select the correct account and post the payment by clicking the Save icon.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  \r Reconciling cash accounts \r Viewing the balance of a cash account\r \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r   Deposit Slips \r &nbsp;'),(340,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/04-Reconcilliation/ReconcilliationHome.html','07.05.04','Banking - Account Reconciliation','Banking - Account Reconciliation     Banking - Account Reconciliation Account reconciliation balances the phreebooks cash account with your financial institution.  Account Reconciliation    Open the account reconciliation screen by selecting Banking-&gt;Account Reconciliation.   Select the cash account to reconcile.   enter the ending balance in the Statement Ending Balance&nbsp;box. The unreconciled amount will appear in the Unreconciled Difference box.    Check the box next to the item as cleared that appear on you financial institutions statement.    After checking all cleared items, the Unreconciled difference should be zero. If not recheck you checked boxes with your statement and correct any errors.   Press the Save icon to save your changes.'),(341,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/05-Banking/BankingHome.html','07.05','Banking','Banking Home     Banking Phreebooks tracks customer payments and payments to vendors.  The following services are available in PhreeBooks: Customer Receipts - Checks, credit cards, and EFTs from your customers. Vendor Payments - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.   Bank Account Reconciliation - Reconcile PhreeBooks cash accounts with you financial institution. &nbsp;'),(342,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/05-Purchases/PurchasesHome.html','07.02.05','Vendors - Purchases','Vendors - Purchases\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Purchase/Receive\r Vendor purchases are represented as inventory items, services and other bills received related to operating your company. Purchases affect the financial picture of your company. All purchase records are maintained in the purchase/receive journal. \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a purchase order\r    Receiving inventory from a purchase order \r    Receiving inventory directly from vendors\r   Editing a purchase/receive\r   Deleting a purchase/receive \r   Checking vendor balances \r Inventory\r Adding inventory items\r Banking\r Paying a bill - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.\r Writing a check to a vendor.\r Reports\r Checking inventory balances\r   Vendor history report\r \r &nbsp;'),(343,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/05-Purchases/01-ReceivePO.html','07.02.05.01','Vendors - Receiving a PO','Receive Inventory from a Purchase Order\r \r \r \r \r Receive Inventory from a Purchase Order \r Vendor purchases are represented as inventory items, services and other bills received related to operating your company. Purchases affect the financial picture of your company. All purchase records are maintained in the purchase/receive journal. \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a purchase order\r   Receiving inventory directly from vendors\r   Editing a purchase/receive\r   Deleting a purchase/receive \r Inventory\r Entering inventory items \r Banking\r Paying a bill - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.\r Writing a check to a vendor.\r Related Reports\r Checking inventory balances\r   Checking vendor account balances\r &nbsp;'),(344,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/05-Purchases/02-ReceiveInv.html','07.02.05.02','Vendors - Receipts from a vendor','Receive Inventory Directly from a Vendor\r \r \r \r \r Receive Inventory Directly from a Vendor\r Inventory can be received directly form a vendor without a purchase order against the vendor account. \r &nbsp;\r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a purchase order\r   Receiving inventory from a purchase order \r   Editing a purchase/receive\r   Deleting a purchase/receive \r Inventory\r Entering inventory items \r Banking\r Paying a bill - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.\r Writing a check to a vendor.\r Related Reports\r Checking inventory balances\r   Checking vendor account balances\r &nbsp;'),(345,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/06-Payments/PaymentsHome.html','07.02.06','Vendors - Payments','Vendors - Payments     Vendors - Payments Paying a vendor for products purchased.'),(346,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Contacts/02-EditContact.html','07.02.02.02','Editing Vendor Contacts','Editing a Vendor Contact\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Vendor Contact\r To edit a vendor record:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the vendor to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the vendor.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the vendor.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor contact \r   Deleting a vendor contact \r Setting up a vendor credit limit\r Purchase Orders\r Entering  a purchase order\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r \r &nbsp;'),(347,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Contacts/ContactsHome.html','07.02.02','Vendors - Contacts','Vendors - Contacts\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Contacts \r Vendor contacts contain information about your suppliers of inventory, services and other purchases required for your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete vendor contacts is similar to that for customers within PhreeBooks. \r Vendor Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for purchase account and terms; customizable  for each individual vendor\r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individaul purchase rep default assignment \r   Freee-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Deleting a vendor \r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase  Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r   Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balance\r &nbsp;'),(348,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Contacts/01-NewContact.html','07.02.02.01','Entering Vendor Contacts','Entering a Vendor Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Vendor Contact \r Vendor contacts include any outside organization that you acquire goods or services from. Generally, they are organizations that you make payments to. \r NOTE: Vendor contacts may be created at time of purchase by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Purchase/Receive, Payment or Purchase Order form. In this case, an unique contact ID must be entered and the contact will be created using the standard terms, default Purchase GL account, no User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses. \r To create a new contact:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;New Vendor or Select the New icon form the Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r    Enter an unique Vendor ID. The Vendor ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this vendor form all other vendors. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact  and Main Mailing (billing) Address information. Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default purchase account. This is typically an accounts payable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this vendor. \r   Enter your account number with this vendor. This number can be used for purchase orders, checks to reference your account to the vendor.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the vendor can ship from multiple locations, additional ship from addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a vendor but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the vendor. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a vendor by vendor basis. \r   If the vendor has additional remit to (billing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a vendor but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r   Updating a vendor contact\r   Deleting a vendor contact\r Setting up a vendor credit limit\r Purchase Orders\r Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Purchase/Receive Inventory \r Receiving items from a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r   Checking vendor balances'),(349,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Contacts/03-DeleteContact.html','07.02.02.03','Deleting Vendor Contacts','Deleting a Vendor Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Contact \r NOTE: Vendors cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a vendor record:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the vendor to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the vendor.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor contact \r Editing a vendor contact \r Purchase Orders\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r \r &nbsp;'),(350,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Contacts/04-PaymentTerms.html','07.02.02.04','Vendor Payment Terms','Vendor Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Vendor Payment Terms\r Vendor payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new vendor contacts. Additionally, existing contacts with out terms defined (or \'Use Standard Terms\') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual vendor terms may also be set up for vendors whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific purchases through the Purchase Order/Purchase procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Vendor Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default vendor credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Vendor Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select  Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors. \r   Search for the vendor whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this vendor.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current vendor.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Purchase/Receive (or Purchase Order, Vendor Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor contact\r Editing a vendor contact\r Purchase Orders\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balance\r &nbsp;'),(351,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/01-General/GeneralHome.html','07.02.01','Vendors - General Information','Vendors - General Information     Vendors - General Information This section covers the activites realted to your vendors. Accounts -  Purchase Orders -  Quotes -  Purchases -  Payments -  POP -  Credit Memos -  Vendor Status -'),(352,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/06-POP/POPHome.html','07.02.06','Vendors - Point of Purchase','Vendors - Point of Purchase     Vendors - Point of Purchase Point of purchase is the process of receiving an item and applying a payment at the time of acquisition.'),(353,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/09-POP/POPHome.html','07.02.09','Vendors - Point of Purchase','Vendors - Point of Purchase     Vendors - Point of Purchase Point of purchase is the process of receiving an item and applying a payment at the time of acquisition.'),(354,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/VendorHome.html','07.02','Vendors','Vendors Home\r \r \r \r \r Vendors Home\r Vendors are your suppliers of products and services.  They are used in PhreeBooks to represent people or companies that payments are made to.  This will include suppliers of your inventory items, governmental organizations for tax payments, services provided to your company (shipping companies, payroll, utilities, professional services, etc) and other expense related accounts.  Generally, vendors include anyone that you make payments to.\r PhreeBooks uses a single database table to hold employee, branch, vendor and customer account information. \r Vendor account features include:\r \r   Fields for main account address along with unlimited branch billing addresses and shipping addresses.\r   Default general ledger settings for purchases\r   2 main telephone numbers, 1 fax number, email and website fields\r   Customer account number\r   Government ID (FEIN) Number\r   Discount and Payment terms specific to an account\r \r Security Settings\r Related Topics:\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a vendor account\r   Deleting a vendor account\r   Editing a vendor account\r   Setting default payment terms \r   Adding branch and shipping addresses\r Vendor Quotes \r  Enter a vendor Request for Quote  (RFQ) \r   Edit a vendor Request for Quote (RFQ)\r   Delete a vendor Request for Quote\r   (RFQ)\r   Convert a request for quote to a Purchase Order\r Purchase Orders\r  Enter a vendor purchase order (PO) \r   Edit a vendor purchase order (PO)\r   Delete a vendor purchase order (PO)\r   Receive inventory from a purchase order (PO Manager)\r Vendor Purchases and Payments \r Receive inventory\r  Paying a bill - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.\r  Receiving inventory from a vendor \r Payments by credit card \r Vendor Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r   Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Reports and Forms \r Standard vendor reports\r   Standard vendor forms\r &nbsp;'),(355,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/04-Quotes/01-EnterQuote.html','07.02.04.01','Entering Vendor Request for Quote','Entering Vendor Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Vendor Request for Quote\r Request for Quote are used to enter purchase from a vendor. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Request for Quotes do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load.\r   Enter the Vendor ID and click on the open icon right of the Vendor ID window. The vendor popup window will appear. Select the vendor from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the request for quote form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Vendor ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find vendors.\r     \r     Vendor records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this request for quote.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the request for quote Post Date and expected Receipt Date. Popup calendars are provided to help with the selection.\r    request for quote Number - Enter the request for quote number. If left blank, the next sequential request for quote number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the your purchase reference   number, store id and purchase representative. The default accounts payable account is loaded and can be changed. The vendor payment terms are loaded when a vendor is selected from the vendor popup. If a new vendor is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this request for quote and press Save to enter the terms into the request for quote form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the request for quote. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the request for quote form. Enter the quantity requested. The item cost value assigned to the sku will be placed in the price field and the line total will be calculated. \r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the request for quote. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the request for quote number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the request for quote will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Updating vendor information\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Vendor Request for Quote\r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r     Editing a request for quote\r     Deleting a request for quote  \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r     Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates'),(356,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/04-Quotes/QuotesHome.html','07.02.04','Vendors - Request for Quotes','Vendors - Request for Quotes\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Request for Quotes\r Request for Quote are used to enter purchase from a vendor. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Request for Quotes do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r Vendor Request for Quote features:\r \r   Multiple inventory line items \r   Separate billing and shipping address \r   Drop ship ability \r    Individual general ledger accounts for each line item\r   Freight estimator to calculate shipping costs\r   Sales tax can be added to PO \r   Customizable payment terms\r \r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Updating vendor information\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Vendor Request for Quote\r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Editing a request for quote\r   Deleting a request for quote \r \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r &nbsp;'),(357,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/04-Quotes/02-EditQuote.html','07.02.04.02','Editing Vendor Request for Quote','Editing a Vendor Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Editing a Vendor Request for Quote\r Vendor purchase  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Updating vendor information\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Vendor Request for Quote\r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r     Editing a request for quote\r     Deleting a request for quote  \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r  Writing a check to a vendor\r     Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r &nbsp;'),(358,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/04-Quotes/03-DeleteQuote.html','07.02.04.03','Deleting Vendor Request for Quote','Deleting a Vendor Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Request for Quote\r Purchase  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the comfirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Updating vendor information\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Vendor Request for Quote\r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r     Editing a request for quote\r     Deleting a request for quote  \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r     Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r &nbsp;'),(359,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/01-EnterPO.html','07.02.03.01','Entering Purchase Orders','Entering Customer Purchase Orders\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Vendor Purchase Orders\r Purchase orders are used to enter purchase from a vendor. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Purchase orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Purchase Orders. The Purchase Order form will load.\r   Enter the Vendor ID and click on the open icon right of the Vendor ID window. The vendor popup window will appear. Select the vendor from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Purchase Order form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Vendor ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find vendors.\r     \r     Vendor records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this purchase order.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the purchase order Post Date and expected Receipt Date. Popup calendars are provided to help with the selection.\r    Purchase Order Number - Enter the purchase order number. If left blank, the next sequential purchase order number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the your purchase reference   number, store id and purchase representative. The default accounts payable account is loaded and can be changed. The vendor payment terms are loaded when a vendor is selected from the vendor popup. If a new vendor is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this purchase order and press Save to enter the terms into the purchase order form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the purchase order. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the purchase order form. Enter the quantity requested. The item cost value assigned to the sku will be placed in the price field and the line total will be calculated. \r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the purchase order. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the purchase order will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Editing a vendor account \r     Deleting a vendor account\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Writing a check to a vendor.\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator'),(360,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/POHome.html','07.02.03','Vendors - Purchase Orders','Vendors - Purchase Orders\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Purchase Orders\r Purchase orders are used to enter inventory and services purchased from a vendor. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Purchase orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r Purchase Order features:\r \r   Multiple inventory line items \r   Separate billing and shipping address \r   Drop ship ability \r    Individual general ledger accounts for each line item\r   Freight estimator to calculate shipping costs\r   Sales tax can be added to PO \r   Customizable payment terms\r \r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r   Editing a vendor account \r   Deleting a  vendor account\r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r    Editing a purchase order\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r   Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r Writing a check to a vendor\r     Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r &nbsp;'),(361,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/04-POManager.html','07.02.03.04','Purchase Order Manager','Purchase Order Manager\r \r \r \r \r Purchase Order Manager\r The purchase order manager lists all open purchase orders in the current accounting period. From this screen, the purchase order may be reviewed, inventory items may be received, and item delivery dates may be entered. The search period pull-down menu and the text search box are available to quickly locate purchase orders.\r Viewing a Purchase Order\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Purchase Order Manager\r   Locate the purchase order to view and press the button labeled View.\r   The Purchase Order screen will load and the form will be filled in with the information of the selected PO.\r   From here, the purchase order may be edited, deleted,  closed or reviewed. \r \r Receiving Inventory from a Purchase Order\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Purchase Order Manager \r   Locate the purchase order to receive against and press the button labeled \'Receive\'.\r   The Purchase/Receive screen will load and the remaining items from the selected PO will be shown.\r   Receive in the quantities received for each line item.\r    Make any other changes as necessary; such as the vendors invoice number or check the Waiting for Invoice if the invoice has not been received.\r   Press the Save icon to save the inventory receipt.\r \r Changing Delivery Dates for a Purchase Order\r When a purchase order is placed, the expected delivery date is set based on the  Lead Time field specific to the inventory item. After a PO is sent to a vendor, the vendors delivery dates may not align with the items Lead Time date. the estimated delivery dates may be modified here to reflect the current estimated delivery dates for each line item on the PO. the delivery dates field is useful to identify when items are expected for filling back-orders and notifications of expected arrivals of inventory items.\r \r    Select Vendors-&gt;Purchase Order Manager \r   Locate the purchase order to adjust or view the expected delivery dates and press the button labeled \'Delivery Dates\'.\r   A popup will appear listing each line item from the PO, the quantity ordered and the description. The currently expected delivery date will also be displayed.\r   If necessary, enter a new delivery date for each item on the PO. A popup calendar is provided to help locate dates. If no change is necessary, leave the date field blank to retain the current delivery date. \r   After updating all affected delivery dates, press the Save icon the save the changes and return to the Purchase Order Manager window. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Editing a vendor account \r     Deleting a vendor account\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Reports and Forms \r Open purchase order report'),(362,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/05-ClosePO.html','07.02.03.05','Closing Purchase Orders','Closing a Vendor Purchase Order\r \r \r \r \r Closing a Vendor Purchase Order\r Purchase  orders can  be closed for several reasons. They may be closed directly from the Edit PO screen by selecting the close button.Closed POs will not affect the inventory levels or appear in any inventory stock level calculations. POs may also be closed by PhreeBooks if all the items have been received through the Purchase/Receive screen. Closing a purchase order will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory identified in the purchase order being closed that have not been received. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Purchase Orders. The Purchase Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the purchase orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be closed and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r   \r   Check the Close selection box.\r   Press the Save button.\r \r When a purchase order is closed, the  quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a purchase order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Editing a vendor account \r     Deleting a vendor account\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r &nbsp;'),(363,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/03-DeletePO.html','07.02.03.03','Deleting Purchase Orders','Deleting a Customer Purchase Order\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Purchase Order\r Purchase  orders can only be deleted if no items have been received from the purchase order. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the purchase order can be deleted. In this case, the purchase order should be closed. See Closing a Purchase Order. Closing a purchase order will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Purchase Orders. The Purchase Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the purchase orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a purchase order is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a purchase order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Editing a vendor account \r     Deleting a vendor account\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Editing a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances'),(364,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/03-PurchaseOrders/02-EditPO.html','07.02.03.02','Editing Purchase Orders','Editing a Vendor Purchase Order\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Vendor Purchase Order\r Purchase  orders can only be edited if no items have been received from the purchase order. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the purchase order can be edited. In this case, the purchase order should be closed. See Closing a Purchase Order. Closing a purchase order will remove all remaining \'quantity on  order\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Purchase Orders. The Purchase Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the purchase orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be edited and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r   \r   Make any necessary changes. Item rows may not be changed if some or all have been received.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes.\r \r When a purchase order is saves, the journal entry is re-posted to the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a purchase order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a new vendor \r     Editing a vendor account \r     Deleting a vendor account\r     Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r     Deleting a purchase order\r     Closing a purchase order\r     Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r     Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r  Writing a check to a vendor\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator'),(365,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/08-Status/StatusHome.html','07.02.08','Vendors - Status','Vendors - Status     Vendors - Status Status of the vendor account.'),(366,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Accounts/02-EditAccount.html','07.02.02.02','Editing Vendor Account','Editing a Vendor Account\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Vendor Account\r To edit a vendor record:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the vendor to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the vendor.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the vendor.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor account \r   Deleting a vendor account \r Setting up a vendor credit limit\r Purchase Orders\r Entering  a purchase order\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r \r &nbsp;'),(367,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Accounts/01-NewAccount.html','07.02.02.01','Entering Vendor Account','Entering a Vendor Account\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Vendor Account \r Vendor accounts include any outside organization that you acquire goods or services from. Generally, they are organizations that you make payments to. \r NOTE: Vendor accounts may be created at time of purchase by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Purchase/Receive, Payment or Purchase Order form. In this case, an unique account ID must be entered and the account will be created using the standard terms, default Purchase GL account, no User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses. \r To create a new account:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;New Vendor or Select the New icon form the Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r    Enter an unique Vendor ID. The Vendor ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this vendor form all other vendors. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact  and Main Mailing (billing) Address information. Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default purchase account. This is typically an accounts payable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this vendor. \r   Enter your account number with this vendor. This number can be used for purchase orders, checks to reference your account to the vendor.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the vendor can ship from multiple locations, additional ship from addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a vendor but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the vendor. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a vendor by vendor basis. \r   If the vendor has additional remit to (billing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a vendor but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r   Updating a vendor account\r   Deleting a vendor account\r Setting up a vendor credit limit\r Purchase Orders\r Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Purchase/Receive Inventory \r Receiving items from a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r   Checking vendor balances'),(368,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Accounts/03-DeleteAccount.html','07.02.02.03','Deleting Vendor Account','Deleting a Vendor Account\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Account \r NOTE: Vendors cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a vendor record:\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the vendor to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the vendor.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Vendors page. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor account \r Editing a vendor account \r Purchase Orders\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balances\r \r &nbsp;'),(369,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Accounts/AccountsHome.html','07.02.02','Vendors - Accounts','Vendors - Accounts\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Accounts \r Vendor accounts contain information about your suppliers of inventory, services and other purchases required for your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete vendor accounts is similar to that for customers within PhreeBooks. \r Vendor Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for purchase account and terms; customizable for each individual vendor\r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individual purchase rep default assignment \r   Free-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Deleting a vendor \r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Purchase  Orders\r Entering a purchase order\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Checking purchase order status (Purchase Order Manager) \r Purchases/Receive Inventory\r Receiving inventory from a purchase order\r   Receiving inventory directly from a vendor\r Other Vendor Actions \r Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Writing a check to a vendor\r   Issuing a vendor credit memo\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balance\r &nbsp;'),(370,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/02-Accounts/04-PaymentTerms.html','07.02.02.04','Vendor Payment Terms','Vendor Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Vendor Payment Terms\r Vendor payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new vendor accounts. Additionally, existing accounts with out terms defined (or \'Use Standard Terms\') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual vendor terms may also be set up for vendors whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific purchases through the Purchase Order/Purchase procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Vendor Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default vendor credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Vendor Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select  Vendors-&gt;Maintain Vendors. \r   Search for the vendor whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this vendor.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current vendor.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Vendors-&gt;Purchase/Receive (or Purchase Order, Vendor Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r  Adding a new vendor account\r Editing a vendor account\r Purchase Orders\r   Deleting a purchase order\r   Closing a purchase order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking vendor balance\r &nbsp;'),(371,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/CreditsHome.html','07.02.07','Vendors - Credit Memos','Vendors - Credit Memos\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r   Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r &nbsp;'),(372,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/03-DeleteCrdMemo.html','07.02.07.03','Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo','Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the invoice. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the invoice can be deleted. In this case, the invoice should be closed. See Closing a Credit Memo. Closing a invoice will remove all remaining \'quantity on invoice\' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the credit memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be deleted and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will affect the income statement and balance sheet since a credit memo represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r     Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Closing a credit memo'),(373,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/02-EditCrdMemo.html','07.02.07.02','Editing a Vendor Credit Memo','Editing a Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Vendor Credit Memo\r Editing an invoice can be performed at any time.\r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Credit Memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be edited and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Enter any changes, as needed, to the credit memo. If any line items from the credit memo have been shipped, that particular line item cannot be deleted or the SKU changed.\r   Press the Save button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is re-posted in the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will  affect the income statement and balance sheet since a invoice represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Checking vendor balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r   Shipping an invoice\r Credit Memos \r Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r    Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)'),(374,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch07-UsersManual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/01-EnterCrdMemo.html','07.02.07.01','Entering a Vendor Credit Memo','Entering Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Vendor Credit Memos\r Credit Memos are used to enter sales to a vendor. Once a credit memo has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or credit memos can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Credit Memos do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load.\r   Enter the Vendor ID and click on the open icon right of the Vendor ID window. The vendor popup window will appear. Select the vendor from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Credit Memo form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Vendor ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find vendors.\r     \r     Vendor records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this credit memo.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Vendors can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the credit memo Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Credit Memo Number - Enter the credit memo number. If left blank, the next credit memo number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the vendors purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The vendor payment terms are loaded when a vendor is selected from the vendor popup. If a new vendor is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this credit memo and press Save to enter the terms into the credit memo form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the credit memo. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the credit memo form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the credit memo. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the credit memo will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Checking vendor balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Credit Memos\r Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Receiving a credit memo\r Reports\r Printing a credit memo'),(375,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch08-HowTo/HowTo-BegBalances.html','08.10','Beginning Balances - Setup','How To ... Beginning Balances     How To ... Setup Beginning Balances  &nbsp;'),(376,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch08-HowTo/HowTo-ZenCart.html','08.04.01','ZenCart Interface','How To ... ZenCart Interface\r \r \r \r \r How To ... Setup the ZenCart Interface\r PhreeBooks has a built in interface with the ZenCart e-commerce shopping cart. The interface provide the following functionality:\r \r   Download orders from Zencart to PhreeBooks\r   Upload products to ZenCart from PhreeBooks \r \r Pre-requisites\r  Order Download Function - None \r Inventory Upload Function - Additional inventory fields are required to match up with the fields used in ZenCart. It is recommended that a new inventory category be added containing the fields needed for the ZenCart interface.\r \r   \r     Field Name\r     (case sensitive) \r     Field Type \r     Description\r   \r   \r     catalog\r     Checkbox\r     Used to identify products that can be uploaded to ZenCart. If the checkbox is selected, an icon will appear allowing the pdoduct to be uploaded to ZenCart. \r   \r   \r     category_id\r     TextField\r     Needs to match exactly with the category as defined in ZenCart. The ZenCart category must be the lowest level in the category tree. \r   \r   \r     manufacturer\r     TextField\r     Needs to match exactly with the manufacturer as defined in ZenCart.\r   \r \r Installing the files in ZenCart \r At the ZenCart enable website, the PhreeSoft PhreeBooks-ZenCart module needs to be installed. the package is available at the PhreeBooks website and the ZenCart website.\r \r   Unzip the files into the Zencart folder and follow the installation instructions. \r   Install the functions desired.\r   Configure the functions per the module installation instructions. When pointing the ZenCart download functions, use url: https://yourdomain.com/PhreeBooksDir/modules/soap/(function).php. i.e. order.php for downloaded orders. (HTTP:// may be used for non-SSL transactions) \r \r Installing the ZenCart Module \r \r   From the Tools -&gt; ZenCart Interface menu select the function to activate and press Install.\r   Press edit to set the parameters for the interface function (see each function detail below for parameters to set).\r   After the parameters have been set, press Update to save the changes.\r \r Setting the function parameters\r Order Download Function \r \r   After installing the function. The only parameters to set are the enable/disable checkbox and the sort order. \r \r Inventory Upload Function \r \r   Install the function if not already installed. \r   Press the Edit button to enter edit mode.\r   Click the enable checkbox.\r   Set the sort order to a non-zero value.\r    For the PhreeBooks XML URL, enter https://yourdomain.com/ZencartDir/admin/soap/products.php.\r   Enter an admin username and password. This can be an existing user, or better, a new user whose activity can be monitored in the admin log file.\r   If price sheets are to be used to set the upload pricing, set the True radsio button and then select a price sheet from the pull down menu. NOTE: At least one price sheet needs to be defined to upload using price sheets. If price sheets are not used, the Retail or Full Price will be used.\r \r Using the ZenCart Functions \r Order Download Function\r \r   Orders can b downloaded by logging into your Zencart shoppping cart and selecting Customers -&gt; Orders. From the order screen an icon will be added indicating whether an order has been downloaded or not. If not, press the icon and the order will be downloaded to PhreeBooks (as a sales order) and the order page will reload. The download icon for the order downloaded will not be shown indicating the order was successfully downloaded to PhreeBooks. \r   If there are download errors during the process, an error message will be displayed. Fix the error and retry. \r \r Inventory Upload Function\r \r   Select Inventory -&gt; Maintain. The list of inventory items will be displayed with an upload icon appearing next to the products that have been identified as catalog items. (Catalog items are items that have the added inventory field catalog checked)\r   If there are upload errors during the process, an error message will be displayed. Fix the error and retry. \r \r Additional Information\r Adding Inventory Categories\r Adding Inventory Fields Adding Price Sheets\r &nbsp;'),(377,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch08-HowTo/HowToHome.html','08','How To ...','How To ...     How To ... Installation &nbsp; Company Setup &nbsp; Receivables &nbsp; Payables &nbsp; Inventory &nbsp; Banking &nbsp; General Ledger &nbsp; Employees &nbsp; Importing/Exporting &nbsp; Reports and Forms  &nbsp;'),(378,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch08-HowTo/HowTo-SalesProcess.html','08.03.01','Process a Sale','How To ... Process a Sale\r \r \r \r \r How To ... Process a Sale \r Processing sales are a key part of the phreebooks capabilities. Prior to processing a sale there are many settings that are required. \r Pre-requisites:\r Inventory - Need something to sell\r   Customer - Someone to sell to (Note - Customers can be added on either the Sales Order or Sales/Invoice screen by checking the add/update button)\r   Sales Tax Authorities and Rates \r   Payment Methods - Cash and bank Check are loaded by default\r   Shipping Carriers - If shipping is necessary. FreeShipper is installed by default and can be used when no shipping is needed.\r Entering a Sale - The Process \r OPTIONAL - Customers -&gt; Customer Quote. The customer quote is optional and if entered, can be converted to a sales order or invoice. (conversion available in Release R1.4 and up) \r OPTIONAL - Customers -&gt; Sales Order. Enter the customer information or select from the popup menu. Required fields are indicated with a red star. Select the items to sell, price. Enter the tax (automatically calculated from pull down) and shipping carrier/method.\r Customers -&gt; Sales/Invoice. If a Sales Order was created, enter the customer name in the search box and press the open icon. The customer should be in the popup menu with a pull down showing all open sales orders. Select the sales order from the pull down or select Enter New to create a new sales/Invoice. All the information will be entered in the Sales/Invoice screen. If a Sales/Invoice will be generated new in this screen enter the information for both the billing and shipping required fields and enter the item(s) being purchased. Enter the tax and shipping carrier/methods. Leave the invoice number blank and PhreeBooks will assign the next invoice number from the sequence. \r NOTE: The invoice may be printed here but will show a balance due. If a payment is to be received (Point of Sale), it is better to receive the payment and print out the receipt after the payment has been processed show the invoice shows the payment applied. \r Option 1: No payment received at this time (customer billed).\r Click on the pdf icon to print the invoice and/or packing slip. Only one form may be printed at a time. If an invoice and a packing slip are both needed, print one, open the invoice again and print the other. \r Option 2: Payment received\r Click on the payment icon (looks like a calculator) and the invoice will be posted and the Customer Receipts screen will appear. Enter the payment information and click the pdf icon to print the invoice with the payment showing.\r NOTE: To aid in reconciliation with the bank, code the Deposit Ticket ID in a way such that similar type are grouped together. For example, if you accept Visa, code all receipts using Visa as payment with a VISAyyyymmdd and they will be grouped together in the bank reconciliation operation to match with the credit card batch. Code checks DPyyyymmdd and all checks received (or part of a bank deposit) will be totaled and displayed as a single line item in the reconciliation screen. All checks that are part of a single bank deposit should have the same Deposit Ticket ID code. This technique aligns the  Deposit Slip report and the bank statements. Same with credit card batches (daily credit card receipts) and cash (to count the cash drawer at the end of the day).\r To ship the item, press Customers-&gt; Invoice Manager. Locate the invoice and press the Ship button. A popup will appear for the carrier selected. For most of the basic shipping carriers, a form to enter the tracking number, if any, and date will be displayed. This information is entered into the shipping log. For package carriers such as UPS or FedEx, the shipping screen will appear to enter the package information. Once entered, shipping labels will be generated and can be printed (on either plain paper through pdf format or thermal label printer). For these carriers, the shipping log will be filled in automatically after the labels have been generated and the tracking information is known.\r NOTE: To re-print the labels or track the package, press Tools -&gt; Shipping and select the tab of the carrier. \r &nbsp;'),(379,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/02-02-SSLFactors.html','03.02.02','SSL Considerations','To SSL or not to SSL     To SSL or not to SSL PhreeBooks can run in either an secure SSL environment or non-SSL environment. Although it is not necessary to determine in which mode to operate prior to running the setup script, it is prefered. Changing the operating mode is possible by editting the includes/configure.php file.'),(380,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/02-01-ChartOfAccounts.html','03.02.01','Example Chart of Accounts','Example Chart of Accounts\r \r \r \r \r  Chart of Accounts\r PhreeBooks contains several example chart of accounts that can be entered during setup. There is also a provision to import your own chart of accounts during the set-up process. Your custom chart of accounts file should be placed into the directory /modules/install/charts before the setup script is executed. The file requirements are as follows:\r File Type: Text (.php extension)\r   Format: php syntax as follows:\r Comments -  preceeded by a //\r   Variable $chart_description - defines the title of the chart of accounts\r   Autoincrement Array Variable $chart_array - contains three elements (1) Account Number (alphanumeric), (2) Description, (3) Account_type code.\r The Account types are:\r 0 - Cash\r   2 - Accounts Receivable\r   4 - Inventory\r   6 - Other Current Assets\r   8 - Fixed Assets\r   10 - Accumulated Depreciation\r   12 - Other Assets\r   20 - Accounts Payable\r   22 - Other Current Liabilities\r   24 - Long Term Liabilities\r   30 - Income\r   32 - Cost of Sales\r   34 - Expenses\r   40 - Equity - Doesn\\\'t Close\r   42 - Equity - Gets Closed\r   44 - Equity - Retained Earnings\r \r The example below is a snippet from the USA General Retail chart of accounts: \r &lt;?php\r   // Chart of Accounts for USA simple General company\r   $chart_description = &quot;US - General store simple Chart of Accounts&quot;;\r $chart_array = array();\r $chart_array[] = array(\'1060\',\'Checking Account\',\'0\');\r   $chart_array[] = array(\'1065\',\'Petty Cash\',\'0\');\r   $chart_array[] = array(\'1200\',\'Accounts Receivables\',\'2\');\r   $chart_array[] = array(\'1205\',\'Allowance for doubtful accounts\',\'2\');\r   \r .\r .\r .\r $chart_array[] = array(\'5800\',\'Licenses\',\'34\');\r $chart_array[] = array(\'5810\',\'Foreign Exchange Loss\',\'34\');\r ?&gt;'),(381,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/01-PreRequisites.html','03.01','Pre-requisites','Pre-requisites     Pre-requisites Prior to running the setup script. the following items need to be verified: System Requirements  During the setup script, PhreeBooks will inspect your system and let you know of any missing or downlevel pre-requisites. The setup script will not continue until these pre-requisites are met.    Mysql Version: 4.0 or higher    PHP Version: 5.0 and higher   Customization Requirements     To load your own chart of accounts (versus one of the example charts), a file needs to be generated and put into the /modules/install/charts directory. Refer to the chart of accounts help file for format information.'),(382,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/05-InstallationFAQ.html','03.05','Installation FAQs','Common Installation Problems and Frequently Asked Questions     Common Installation Problems and FAQs Below are some of the common errors installing phreebooks. More current information can also be found at the PhreeBooks support site, http://www.phreebooks.com/pb_phpBB/index.php. Table of Contents    Issue 1   Issue 2  Resolutions         Issue 1            Resolution 1                Issue 2            Resolution 2      &nbsp;'),(383,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/02-PreInstallInfo.html','03.02','Pre-installation Required Information','Pre-installation Required Information     Pre-installation Required Information User the following checklist to help in verifying you have all the information necesary prior to running the setup script.         Complete     Description           &nbsp;     Download and unpack the necessary files            &nbsp;     Upload the files to your server in the desired directory           &nbsp;     Create the database table (note the database name, username, and user password)                &nbsp;     &nbsp;           &nbsp;     &nbsp;           &nbsp;     &nbsp;           &nbsp;     &nbsp;           &nbsp;     &nbsp;           &nbsp;     &nbsp;     &nbsp;'),(384,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/InstallationHome.html','03','Installation','Installation     Installation The section deals with installation concerns from downloading the distribution to post-installation. The Setup section contains information from the intial  login screen to intializing company information, setting users, permissions, etc. Installation topics:  Pre-installation    Pre-Requisites   Chart of Accounts    SSL Considerations   Pre-installation Checklist   The Setup Script     Running the setup script   Post-Installation    Transferring data   Setting up beginning balances   Installation FAQs    Frequently Asked Questions'),(385,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/03-SetupScript.html','03.03','Running the Setup Scirpt','Running the Setup Script     Running the Setup Script Prior to setup you will want to ensure that the directory you are installing to is accessible from a web browser. You will also want to ensure that you have access to a database and have the database name, user name and password.   Unzip file into the desired directory on your server.  In a web browser, go to the location you unzipped the files to. You should receive a message stating that the configure.php was not found and a link to install the program. When you click the link you will be taken to the welcome page.  Welcome You can read read through the information on the welcome page and then click continue.  License Read and accept the user license and click continue.  Prerequisites The installer will now check for the required files and directories. If there are any unmet dependencies that prevent continuing installation these will be shown in a warning box at the top of the page. You can click the \'more info\' link next to unmet dependencies for information on how to fix the problem.  It is common for the MySQL database to be in red since the program may not yet have access to the database. This WIL NOT prevent installation.  You will also want to look at the bottom of the prerequisites page to ensure you have the correct file permissions set.  Once all of the required dependencies are met you can click install at the bottom of the page.  System Setup You will now be  asked the enter the directory or http(s) paths you want to use for various services.  You can change these if you like but the defaults should work for most installations. You will also be asked if you want to enable SSL.  Unless you know you have SSL working and want to use it you should leave this set to \'NO\'.  Select \'Save Settings\' once you have finished filling out all the boxes.  Database Setup Database Type - Select the type of database you are using from the drop down menu.  Database Table - Prefix - In most cases this will be left blank.  You can enter a prefix if you are using a single database for multiple applications.  Database Host - Default is localhost but you may enter another host name or IP address if database is not hosted locally.  Database Username - Username you entered when setting up database.  Database Password - Password you entered when setting up database.  Company Database Name - Enter the name of the database you setup.  Contact the hosting provider if you are unsure.  Admin Setup Enter your Administrator name, password and email.  You can also choose whether you would like to check for updates when logging in.  Company Setup Enter your company\'s information and click save.  Chart of Accounts Choose a chart of accounts most appropriate for your company.  Details of each chart can be viewed by selecting an account type and clicking \'view chart details\' link. Save settings once you have made your selection.  Fiscal Year Setup Choose the date and year you want your fiscal year to begin and save.  Account Defaults PhreeBooks will attempt to determine the correct account numbers for the given items.  This can be changed later but now is a good time to ensure that all of the account numbers are correct for the given items.  Finished Your setup of PhreeBooks is now complete.  This page will provide some information on further steps to help you configure PhreeBooks for your company\'s needs.  Make sure you set permissions on your configure.php, located in the /includes folder, back to read only.  Remove or rename your modules/install folder so that the system cannot be re-installed which would wipe out your existing database.'),(386,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/04-03-TransferingData.html','03.04.03','Transfering Data into PhreeBooks','Transfering data into PhreeBooks     Transfering data into PhreeBooks Data from other sources can be entered, in bulk, to PhreeBooks through the beginning balances functions and the import/export operation. Refer to the particular section for details in their respective operation. Here is the general guideline to transfering data into PhreeBooks.    Complete the setup script to initilize the database. (Be sure to use you current chart of accounts)    Set-up inventory categories and fields.    Import Inventory Items, Customers, Vendors and Employees.   Import beginning Accounts Receivable, Accounts Payable, and Inventory balances.   Edit the beginning balances form to match each account with your former trial balance from the previous accounting package.   Set the current accounting period to the current period.   View the Income Statement and Balance Sheet and compare with the expected account values.'),(387,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/04-01-configPHP.html','03.04.01','Modifying configure.php','Modifying configure.php     Modifying configure.php The file /includes/configure.php contains critical setup information necessary to run PhreeBooks. It is created during the setup process and generally shouldn\'t be touched (except to make it read-only). the following constant variables are set in configure.php during the setup script:    HTTP_SERVER - Main webserver: eg, http://localhost - should not be empty for production servers   HTTPS_SERVER - Secure webserver: eg, https://localhost - should not be empty for production servers   ENABLE_SSL_ADMIN - secure webserver   DIR_WS_ADMIN - url path (these paths are relative to top of your webspace)   DIR_FS_ADMIN - The physical path is a COMPLETE path to your PhreeBooks files.   DEFAULT_LANGUAGE - define the default language (can also be changed at login)    DB_TYPE - databse type (currently only mysql is supported)    DB_PREFIX - If phreebooks shares the database with other applications, a table prefix may be used.  &nbsp;'),(388,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/04-PostInstallation.html','03.04','Post-Installation','Post-Installation Considerations     Post-Installation Considerations After the setup script is complete the following steps should be taken to secure your system.    Change the permissions on includes/configure.php to read-only (0x444).'),(389,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch03-Installation/04-02-BeginningBalances.html','03.04.02','Beginning Balances','Entering Beginning Balances\r \r \r \r \r Entering Beginning Balances\r Unless PhreeBooks is set up on a new company, there will probalby be a need to transfer beginning balances from your old accounting system.   The follwing tables define the data structures required to import inventory valuation and balances as well as Payables and Receivables balances.\r Inventory\r Before beginning balances can be set up, inventory items need to be imported (or entered) into PhreeBooks. Refer to manual pages on importing/exporting data for the procedure and more information.\r NOTE: If any part of the beginning balances needs to be re-entered, the only option at this time is to purge the GL and history records through the General Ledger -&gt; Utilities -&gt; Purge Journal Entries option. Note that purging the journal entries will clean out the journals and history records. It will not affect the customer or vendor accounts. \r File format \r Type: csv (comma separated variables)\r   Delimiter: comma (,)\r   Qualifier: double-quote (&quot;)\r File extension must be .csv or .txt \r Header Lines: 1  (header fields as identifed in the table below)\r Column contents\r Each entry of the inventory beginning balances should have to following information. Required fields are marked with a *. \r \r   \r     Field Name \r     Description\r   \r   \r     *sku\r     The item sku as defined on the inventory database. Must match exactly, case sensitive. \r   \r   \r     *gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to use to offset the inventory value. This account should be an \'equity-doesn\'t close\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     *inv_gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to store the inventory value. This should be and \'inventory\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     *quantity\r     The quantity of the sku to set as the beginning inventory balance.\r   \r   \r     *total_amount\r     The total value of the inventory item in the default currency. The unit cost will be calculated by dividing the total cost by the quantity.\r   \r   \r     &nbsp;\r      Serialized items - cannot be imported at this time \r     \r   \r \r Notes:\r \r    The beginning balances script will verify the sku is valid, GL accounts are valid. If any of these are found to be true, the script will terminate and no entries will be added to the databases. The script will also verify the the quantity is non-zero. If a zero quantity is found, the script will skip the entry and proceed to the next entry.\r \r Purchase Orders \r Importing purchase orders can be performed without first importing the your vendor accounts. The import routine will create the account if it cannot be found. POs with multiple line items must be consecutive to ensure that they are included in the same journal entry. \r File format \r Type: csv (comma separated variables)\r   Delimiter: comma (,)\r   Qualifier: double-quote (&quot;)\r   File extension must be .csv or .txt \r   Header Lines: 1 (header fields as identifed in the table below)\r Column contents\r Each entry of the purchase order should have to following information. Required fields are marked with a *. \r \r   \r     Field Name \r     Description\r   \r   \r     *account_id\r     The Short Name of the vendor that the purchase order should be entered against. This must match exactly to the short name of the vendor existing in the system (or it will be created).\r   \r   \r     *gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to apply the purchase order. This should be an \'accounts payable\' type of account. This account must be the same for all line items of the same PO number. \r   \r   \r     *inv_gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to use for the inventory line item. This account should be an \'inventory\' or \'expense\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     total_amount\r     The total value of the purchase order in the default currency.\r   \r   \r     freight_total\r     The total freight amount of the purchase order.\r   \r   \r     tax_total\r     The total sales tax amount of the purchase order.\r   \r   \r     *order_id\r     Purchase Order  number of this entry. Used for account tracking and payment identification.\r   \r   \r     *post_date\r     Date of the purchase order.\r   \r   \r     *bill_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts mailing address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     bill_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     *bill_address1\r     The first mailing address line.\r   \r   \r     bill_address2\r     The second mailing address line. \r   \r   \r     *bill_city_town\r     The mailing city or town. \r   \r   \r     *bill_state_province\r     The mailing state or province. \r   \r   \r     bill_postal_code\r     The mailing postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     *bill_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r   \r     telephone1\r     The account primary telephone number.\r   \r   \r     telephone2\r     The account altrernate telephone number.\r   \r   \r     fax\r     The account fax number.\r   \r   \r     email\r     The account e-mail address.\r   \r   \r     website\r     The acount website.\r   \r   \r     *sku\r     The line item SKU. Only one SKU per line. \r   \r   \r     *description\r     The line item description of the SKU. \r   \r   \r     *quantity\r     The quantity ordered.\r   \r   \r     *total_cost\r     The line item total price. The unit price will be calculated by (total price / quantity).\r     \r   \r \r Notes:\r \r   The billing information will be used as the bill to address for purchase orders. \r    The script will verify the account (Short Name) is valid (or a new account will be created).\r    GL accounts will be verified.\r   If the post date is not within the currently defined fiscal years (including bad format) the record will be placed in accounting period 1. \r   If any other errors are found, the script will terminate and no entries will be added to the databases. \r   If the beginning balance file is imported successfully, DO NOT REPEAT the import. The new entries will be added to the prior successful import and duplicate the payables. The import operation will not be posted unless the entire file is read in correctly and the success message is displayed.\r   The ship to address is assumed to be the company default address. \r \r Accounts Payable\r Importing payables can be performed without first importing the your vendor accounts. The import routine will create the account if it cannot be found.\r File format \r Type: csv (comma separated variables)\r   Delimiter: comma (,)\r   Qualifier: double-quote (&quot;)\r   File extension must be .csv or .txt \r   Header Lines: 1 (header fields as identifed in the table below)\r Column contents\r Each entry of the accounts payable beginning balances should have to following information. Required fields are marked with a *. \r \r   \r     Field Name \r     Description\r   \r   \r     *account_id\r     The Short Name of the vendor that the purchase order should be entered against. This must match exactly to the short name of the vendor existing in the system (or it will be created).\r   \r   \r     *gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to apply the purchase order. This account should be an \'equity-doesn\'t close\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     *inv_gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to use for the inventory line item. This account should be an \'inventory\' or \'expense\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     *total_amount\r     The total value of the payable in the default currency.\r   \r   \r     freight_total\r     The total freight amount of the purchase order.\r   \r   \r     tax_total\r     The total sales tax amount of the purchase order.\r   \r   \r     order_id\r     Invoice number of this entry. Used for account tracking and payment identification. If left blank, the waiting for invoice box will be checked.\r   \r   \r     *post_date\r     Date of the invoice. Used calculate aging of payables. \r   \r   \r     *bill_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts mailing address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     bill_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     *bill_address1\r     The first mailing address line.\r   \r   \r     bill_address2\r     The second mailing address line. \r   \r   \r     *bill_city_town\r     The mailing city or town. \r   \r   \r     *bill_state_province\r     The mailing state or province. \r   \r   \r     bill_postal_code\r     The mailing postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     *bill_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r   \r     telephone1\r     The account primary telephone number.\r   \r   \r     telephone2\r     The account alternate telephone number.\r   \r   \r     fax\r     The account fax number.\r   \r   \r     email\r     The account e-mail address.\r   \r   \r     website\r     The acount website.\r   \r \r Notes:\r \r   The default company information will be used as the ship to address for payables and only a single line item will be entered identified as \'Beginning Balances Entry\'. \r    The script will verify the account (Short Name) is valid (or a new account will be created).\r    GL accounts will be verified.\r   If the invoice is left blank or null, the Waiting For Payment flag will be set. \r   If the post date is not within the currently defined fiscal years (including bad format) the record will be placed in accounting period 1. \r   The script will verify the the invoice amount is non-zero. If a zero amount is found, the script will skip the entry and proceed to the next entry. In this case, the skipped records will be identified by row number. \r   If any other errors are found, the script will terminate and no entries will be added to the databases. \r   If the beginning balance file is imported successfully, DO NOT REPEAT the import. The new entries will be added to the prior successful import and duplicate the payables. The import operation will not be posted unless the entire file is read in correctly and the success message is displayed.\r   Vendor history accounts will not be updated by this procedure. \r   The ship to address is assumed to be the company default address. \r \r Sales Orders \r Importing sales orders can be performed without first importing the your custoemr accounts. The import routine will create the account if it cannot be found. SOs with multiple line items must be consecutive to ensure that they are included in the same journal entry. \r File format \r Type: csv (comma separated variables)\r   Delimiter: comma (,)\r   Qualifier: double-quote (&quot;)\r   File extension must be .csv or .txt \r   Header Lines: 1 (header fields as identifed in the table below)\r Column contents\r Each entry of the sales order should have to following information. Required fields are marked with a *. \r \r   \r     Field Name \r     Description\r   \r   \r     *account_id\r     The Short Name of the customer that the purchase order should be entered against. This must match exactly to the short name of the customer existing in the system (or it will be created).\r   \r   \r     *gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to apply the sales order. This should be an \'accounts receivable type of account. This account must be the same for all line items of the same sales order number. \r   \r   \r     *inv_gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to use for the inventory line item. This account should be an \'inventory\' or \'expense\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     total_amount\r     The total value of the sales order in the default currency.\r   \r   \r     freight_total\r     The total freight amount of the sales order.\r   \r   \r     tax_total\r     The total sales tax amount of the sales order.\r   \r   \r     *order_id\r     Sales Order number of this entry. Used for account tracking and payment identification.\r   \r   \r     *post_date\r     Date of the sales order.\r   \r   \r     *bill_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts mailing address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     bill_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     *bill_address1\r     The first mailing address line.\r   \r   \r     bill_address2\r     The second mailing address line. \r   \r   \r     *bill_city_town\r     The mailing city or town. \r   \r   \r     *bill_state_province\r     The mailing state or province. \r   \r   \r     bill_postal_code\r     The mailing postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     *bill_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r   \r     telephone1\r     The account primary telephone number.\r   \r   \r     telephone2\r     The account altrernate telephone number.\r   \r   \r     fax\r     The account fax number.\r   \r   \r     email\r     The account e-mail address.\r   \r   \r     website\r     The acount website.\r   \r   \r     ship_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts shipping address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     ship_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     ship_address1\r     The first shipping address line.\r   \r   \r     ship_address2\r     The second shipping address line. \r   \r   \r     ship_city_town\r     The shipping city or town. \r   \r   \r     ship_state_province\r     The shipping state or province. \r   \r   \r     ship_postal_code\r     The shipping postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     ship_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r   \r     *sku\r     The line item SKU. Only one SKU per line. \r   \r   \r     *description\r     The line item description of the SKU. \r   \r   \r     *quantity\r     The quantity ordered.\r   \r   \r     *total_cost\r     The line item total price. The unit price will be calculated by (total price / quantity).\r   \r \r Notes:\r \r   The billing information will be used as the bill to address for sales orders. \r    The script will verify the account (Short Name) is valid (or a new account will be created).\r    GL accounts will be verified.\r   If the post date is not within the currently defined fiscal years (including bad format) the record will be placed in accounting period 1. \r   If the sales order file is imported successfully, DO NOT REPEAT the import. The new entries will be added to the prior successful import and duplicate the sales orders. The import operation will not be posted unless the entire file is read in correctly and the success message is displayed.\r \r Accounts Receivable \r Before beginning balances can be set up, customers need to be imported (or entered) into PhreeBooks. Refer to manual pages on importing/exporting data for the procedure and more information.\r File format \r Type: csv (comma separated variables)\r   Delimiter: comma (,)\r   Qualifier: double-quote (&quot;)\r   File extension must be .csv\r Header Lines: 1 (header fields as identifed in the table below)\r Column contents\r Each entry of the account receivables beginning balances should have to following information. Required fields are marked with a *. \r \r   \r     Field Name \r     Description\r   \r   \r     *account_id\r     The Short Name of the vendor that the invoice should be entered against. This must match exactly to the short name of the vendor existing in the system.\r   \r   \r     *gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to apply the receivable. This should be an \'accounts receivable\' type of account.\r   \r   \r     *inv_gl_acct\r     The General Ledger account ID to use to offset the payable value. This account should be an \'equity-doesn\'t close\' type of account. \r   \r   \r     *total_amount\r     The total value of the receivable in the default currency.\r   \r   \r     freight_total\r     The total freight amount of the invocie.\r   \r   \r     tax_total\r     The total sales tax amount of the invoice.\r   \r   \r     order_id\r     Invoice number of this entry. Used for account tracking and payment identification. If left blank, the waiting for invoice box will be checked.\r   \r   \r     *post_date\r     Date of the invoice. Used calculate aging of payables. \r   \r   \r     *bill_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts mailing address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     bill_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     *bill_address1\r     The first mailing address line.\r   \r   \r     bill_address2\r     The second mailing address line. \r   \r   \r     *bill_city_town\r     The mailing city or town. \r   \r   \r     *bill_state_province\r     The mailing state or province. \r   \r   \r     bill_postal_code\r     The mailing postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     *bill_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r   \r     telephone1\r     The account primary telephone number.\r   \r   \r     telephone2\r     The account alternate telephone number.\r   \r   \r     fax\r     The account fax number.\r   \r   \r     email\r     The account e-mail address.\r   \r   \r     website\r     The acount website.\r   \r   \r     ship_primary_name\r     The primary name of the accounts shipping address. Can be a company name or inidvidual name. \r   \r   \r     ship_contact\r     The contact (or attention) line for the account.\r   \r   \r     ship_address1\r     The first shipping address line.\r   \r   \r     ship_address2\r     The second shipping address line. \r   \r   \r     ship_city_town\r     The shipping city or town. \r   \r   \r     ship_state_province\r     The shipping state or province. \r   \r   \r     ship_postal_code\r     The shipping postal/zip code . \r   \r   \r     ship_country_code\r     The ISO 3 character country code. (USA, CAN, AUS, etc.) \r   \r \r Notes:\r \r    The beginning balances script will verify the account (Short Name) is valid, GL accounts are valid, invoice number exists, and the date is invalid (including bad format). If any of these are found to not match, the script will terminate and no entries will be added to the databases. The script will also verify the the amount is non-zero. If a zero amount is found, the script will skip the entry and proceed to the next entry.\r   If the beginning balance file is imported successfully, DO NOT REPEAT the import. The new entries will be added to the prior successful import and duplicate the receivables. The import operation will not be posted unless the entire file is read in correctly and the success message is displayed.\r   Vendor history accounts will not be updated by this procedure. \r \r &nbsp;'),(390,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch09-Shipping/ShippingHome.html','09','Shipping','Shipping\r \r \r \r \r Shipping\r \r PhreeBooks contains powerful, flexible shipping tools to help estimate, ship, track and monitor your shipping needs. Several shipping modules are included with the standard distribution including FedEx, UPS and USPS along with non-carrier based shipping methods. \r Shipping Manager - The Shipping Manager tool is the main interface to the shipping functions. From here you can ship packages, track packages, review package volume and shipment costs and void shipments. \r Invoice Manager - The Invoice Manager includes a link to the shipping functions to allow for order fulfillment directly from the invoice. The invoice manager does most of the work for you by filling in the shipping form automatically. All you need to do i enter the package information and carrier approved label will be generated within PhreeBooks.\r Related Links\r Shipping Modules\r   Invoice Manager\r  \r &nbsp;'),(391,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch09-Shipping/03-Removal/RemovalHome.html','09.02','Shipping Modules - Removal','Shipping Modules - Removal     Shipping Modules - Removal  There is no need to remove a particular shipping module. Simply uninstalling it will remove the module from appearing in any of PhreeBooks functions.'),(392,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch09-Shipping/01-Modules/table/TableHome.html','09.01.06','Shipping Modules - Table Rate Based Shipping','Shipping Modules - Table Rate Based Shipping\r \r \r \r \r Shipping Modules - Table Rate Based Shipping\r \r PhreeBooks includes a shipping module to calculate table based shipping charges. \r Features Include:\r \r   Freight quotes\r   Shipping Manager integration\r    Customer and Vendor order integration.\r   Integration with Invoice Manger \r   Tracking information and shipping logs \r   Report capability available through reportwriter. \r \r How to Install Table Based Shipping Module \r \r   Through Setup -&gt; Shipping Settings, click on the Table Based row in the table and a button labeled Install will appear on the right. \r   Click on Install to install the Table Based module. \r   Click the Table Based row again and Click on the Edit Button.\r   Enter the rate information and press Save to save the changes. \r \r Note: Place the sort order to a number greater than zero. IF THE SORT ORDER IS ZERO, IT WILL NOT SHOW UP. \r How the Get a Rate Quote\r \r   Rate quotes are available from the order screens. When shipping is enabled (Company -&gt; My Company -&gt; Enable Shipping Settings) a button will appear next to the freight method and price to load the shipping popup and request a rate. \r   The Shipping Quote popup will be mostly filled out with values pulled from the order and the shipping defaults. Changes , however can be made before the carrier servers are queried for rates.\r   Once the information in the shipping popup has been verified, Press the Next button and the rate estimator will pull the quoted rates form the selected services.\r   Click on the rate desired and the carrier, method, and rate information will be entered into the order form; the popup will close. \r \r Note: If the weight field of inventory items is filled out, the weight of the shipment will be automatically calculated and inserted into the rate estimator. \r How to Enter a Shipping Log Record\r \r    Shipping log entries are entered either through the Invoice Manager.\r   From Customers -&gt; Invoice Manger, locate the invoice to create the shipping log entry.\r   Press the Ship button on the line the invoice appears.\r   A popup will appear with a form to enter the package information.\r   Select the Service Type, shipment/Expected receipt dates, tracking information and the shipment cost.\r   Press the Save icon to save the shipment information. NOTE: Once a shipment log entry has been generated, the button on Invoice Manager changes from Ship to Void Shipment.\r \r How to Void a Shipping Log Record\r \r   From Customers -&gt; Invoice Manger, locate the invoice you want to void the shipping log entry.\r   Press the Void Shipment button and the shipping log entry will be deleted. NOTE: The Invoice Manager will now allow the package to be re-shipped if necessary.\r   From Tools -&gt; Shipping Manager, locate the shipment to void.\r   Press the Delete icon on the line of the shipment, confirm the void and the shipment record will be deleted. \r \r How to Track a Package\r \r   From Tools -&gt; Shipping Manager, select the date the package was shipped. Locate the package to track. \r   Since Table Based shipping is not tied to a particular vendor, only the tracking number will be displayed, it can now be copied to the clipboard and pasted into the carrier site to track the package. \r \r Related Subjects\r How to Set up Shipping Defaults\r     Shipping Manager\r     Invoice Manger'),(393,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch09-Shipping/01-Modules/ups/UPSHome.html','09.01.07','Shipping Modules - UPS','Shipping Modules - United Parcel Service (UPS)\r \r \r \r \r Shipping Modules - United Parcel Service (UPS)\r \r PhreeBooks includes a shipping module to integrate with United Parcel Service through their APIs. Companies must have a UPS shipper number and register with UPS.com to request a meter number before the module will function correctly. \r Features Include:\r \r   Freight quotes for Air and Ground small package \r   Label generation for Air and Ground\r   Shipping Manager integration\r    Customer and Vendor order integration.\r   Integration with Invoice Manger \r   Tracking integration\r   Multi-piece shipments \r   Report capability available through reportwriter. \r \r How to Install UPS Shipping\r NOTE: UPs requires a XML Access Key before their servers can be accessed. The access key must be acquired through UPS. Visit UPS.com to request your access key. \r \r   Through Setup -&gt; Shipping Settings, click on the UPS Service row in the table and a button labeled Install will appear on the right. \r   Click on Install to install the UPS module. \r   Click the UPS row again and Click on the Edit Button.\r   Select True to enable the module, enter your UPS account number.  Select Test Mode and your desired Printer Type. Select the services you want to offer and press Update.\r   Enter your UPS  XML Access Key received from UPS. \r   UPS requires sample labels to be mailed to them to validate the quality of the image. Refer to UPS.com for further information.\r   After approval from UPS with your sample labels, Edit the UPS shipping settings and change the Test Mode to Production. \r \r Note: Place the sort order to a number greater than zero. IF THE SORT ORDER IS ZERO, IT WILL NOT SHOW UP. \r How the Get a Rate Quote\r \r   Rate quotes are available from the order screens. When shipping is enabled (Company -&gt; My Company -&gt; Enable Shipping Settings) a button will appear next to the freight method and price to load the shipping popup and request a rate. \r   The Shipping Quote popup will be mostly filled out with values pulled from the order and the shipping defaults. Changes , however can be made before the carrier servers are queried for rates.\r   Once the information in the shipping popup has been verified, Press the Next button and the rate estimator will pull the quoted rates form the selected services.\r   Click on the rate desired and the carrier, method, and rate information will be entered into the order form; the popup will close. \r \r Note: If the weight field of inventory items is filled out, the weight of the shipment will be automatically calculated and inserted into the rate estimator. \r How to Print a Label\r Labels can be printed manually through Shipping Manager or, for a particular invoice, through the Invoice Manager. If Invoice Manager is used, most of the information will be pre-entered into the label form. Verification of information and the package details are all that is needed. If a label is generated from Shipping Manager. the destination address must be entered and the package information.\r From Invoice Manager\r \r   Select Customers -&gt; Invoice Manager. Invoices are listed in descending order by invoice number.\r   Locate the invoice to generate a label from and press the Ship button. NOTE: Once a package has been shipped, the button will change to Void Shipment and the invoice cannot be re-shipped. \r   A popup form will appear with most of the fields filled in. The field information is derived from the invoice itself along with default values set in the Company -&gt; Shipping Defaults settings.\r   Enter the package weight, dimensions and insurance value. If more than one package is to be shipped with this invoice (Multi-piece), press the Plus sign to add another package row. \r   After all information has been entered, press the PDF icon and the label will be retrieved from UPS. \r   Once the label has been retrieved, the window will contain either a button to download the image (thermal printers) or a PDF image will appear in the window.\r   Print the label to the appropriate printer. NOTE: For thermal labels, the label must be printed in RAW format directly to the printer port. In this case, the label must be downloaded and saved locally, The file must then be copied (or moved) directly to the port the thermal printer is connected to. \r   Once all labels have been printed, close the label manager popup widow. \r \r From Shipping Manager\r \r   Select Tools -&gt; Shipping Manager.\r   Click on the Ship a Package button.\r   A popup form will appear with shipping default fields filled in. The field information is derived from the default values set in the Company -&gt; Shipping Defaults settings.\r   Enter the address information to ship the package. \r   Enter the package weight, dimensions and insurance value. If more than one package is to be shipped with this invoice (Multi-piece), press the Plus sign to add another package row. \r   After all information has been entered, press the PDF icon and the label will be retrieved from UPS. \r   Once the label has been retrieved, the window will contain either a button to download the image (thermal printers) or a PDF image will appear in the window.\r   Print the label to the appropriate printer. NOTE: For thermal labels, the label must be printed in RAW format directly to the printer port. In this case, the label must be downloaded and saved locally, The file must then be copied (or moved) directly to the port the thermal printer is connected to. \r   Once all labels have been printed, close the label manager popup widow.\r \r How to Re-Print a Label\r \r    From Tools -&gt; Shipping Manager, locate the package to re-print the label. Click on the printer icon on the package line. NOTE: All labels are stored in the my_files directory on the server. re-printing will not re-query UPS but merely reload the image file from the original request. \r   Once the label has been retrieved (from your local my_files directory), the window will contain either a button to download the image (thermal printers) or a PDF image will appear in the window.\r   Print the label to the appropriate printer. NOTE: For thermal labels, the label must be printed in RAW format directly to the printer port. In this case, the label must be downloaded and saved locally, The file must then be copied (or moved) directly to the port the thermal printer is connected to. \r   Once all labels have been printed, close the label manager popup widow.\r \r How to Void a Shipment\r NOTE: Shipments can only be voided the same day the label was generated. \r \r   Packages can be deleted through either Invoice Manager or Ship Manager. \r   From Invoice Manger, locate the invoice to void the shipment. Press the Void Shipment button and a label void request will be sent to UPS. NOTE: Once a shipment is voided, the button from that invoice in Invoice Manager will revert back to the Ship state where the shipment can be re-shipped if necessary.\r   From Shipping Manager, press the delete icon next to the package you want to void. Confirm the void operation and the shipment will be deleted. NOTE: UPS will only let an entire shipment be deleted, if the shipment contains more than one package, all packages in the shipment will be voided. \r \r How to Track a Package\r \r   From Tools -&gt; Shipping Manager, select the date the package was shipped. Locate the package to track and click on the tracking number. \r   A new window will appear linked to the UPS.com web site and the tracking information will be automatically entered. \r   Packages can also be tracked through the Invoice Manager. Locate the invoice to track, select the View Ship Log icon and a popup will appear with the shipment information. The tracking number will appear in the log, Click on the tracking icon next to it to track the package. \r \r Related Subjects\r How to Set up Shipping Defaults\r     Shipping Manager\r     Invoice Manger'),(394,'http://localhost/phreebooks2/doc/manual/ch09-Shipping/01-Modules/zone/ZoneHome.html','09.01.09','Shipping Modules - State/Province','Shipping Modules - Zone Rates (State/Province)\r \r \r \r \r Shipping Modules - Zone Rates (State/Province)\r \r PhreeBooks includes a shipping module to calculate zone based shipping charges. \r Features Include:\r \r   Freight quotes\r   Shipping Manager integration\r    Customer and Vendor order integration.\r   Integration with Invoice Manger \r   Tracking information and shipping logs \r   Report capability available through reportwriter. \r \r How to Install Zone Based Shipping Module \r \r   Through Setup -&gt; Shipping Settings, click on the Zone Based row in the table and a button labeled Insta